{"title_page": "ACE Moharram Bakhoum", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = ACE Moharram Bakhoum\n| logo                = ACELOGOACELOGO.jpg\n| type                = [[Privately held company]]\n| industry            = [[Engineering]]\n| founder             = [[Ahmed Moharram]] and [[Michel Bakhoum]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Egypt]]\n| num_locations       = Branches in 12 countries\n| area_served         = Worldwide (more than 40 countries)\n| services            = Engineering and Project Management\n| num_employees       = 2100\n| homepage            = http://www.ace-mb.com/\n}}\n'''ACE Moharram Bakhoum''' is a multi-disciplinary [[engineering]] and [[project management]] consultancy company, based in Egypt.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://eklutdvotyzsri.dailynewssegypt.com/2009/12/21/ace-sees-more-opportunities-in-development/|title=ACE sees more opportunities in development|date=2009-12-21|website=Daily News Egypt|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> ACE Moharram Bakhoum offers services in the fields of planning, engineering design, project management and construction supervision of construction-related activities.\n\n== Operations ==\nThe company operates in more than 40 countries, working on both private and publicly financed projects.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Market sectors===\nMarket sectors in which the company operates include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ace-consultants.com/services.htm|title=ACE Consulting Engineers - Services|website=www.ace-consultants.com|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n\n* '''Infrastructure for urban development''' \n** Roads network\n** Earthworks and landscape\n** Wastewater, storm drainage\n** Water, irrigation and fire fighting networks\n** Power supply, street lighting, telecom and data networks\n** District cooling networks\n**Water supply and sewerage\n** Water treatment plants\n** Sewerage treatment plants\n** Pumping stations\n** Transmission pipelines\n** Distribution mains\n** Sewers\n* '''Transportation'''\n** Airports\n** Bridges\n** Roads\n** Tunnels\n** Metro / Rail / Light rail\n* '''Buildings'''\n** Residential\n** Administration\n** Tourist\n** Commercial\n** Cultural\n** Recreation\n** Healthcare\n** Educational\n** Car parks\n* '''Industrial facilities'''\n** Cement plants\n** Fertilizer plants\n** Power plants\n** Petrochemical plants\n** Other industrial facilities\n* '''Irrigation and Hydraulics'''\n** Dams / Barrages\n** Reservoirs\n** Locks\n\n== History ==\nACE Moharram Bakhoum was established in 1950 as a private partnership between [[Ahmed Moharram]] and [[Michel Bakhoum]]. The first projects executed by the partners was a storage area for printing machines constructed in the basement of a building in Cairo, followed by the design of a pharmacological factory. In the 1950s, the partners made their entry into the field of bridge design, for which they later became widely known. By the 1970s, the company witnessed a regional expansion. In 1970, the first phase of the [[6th October Bridge|6th of October Bridge]] was opened. This bridge, which is considered the main artery of the Egyptian capital, was the first [[prestressed concrete]] bridge to be entirely designed, constructed and the construction supervised by Egyptian firms - ACE Moharram Bakhoum was the designer and construction supervisor. By this time, ACE had been involved in numerous high-profile projects in Egypt and the Middle East region, and the expansion of its activities to include other disciplines was necessary.\n\n== Significant projects ==\nExamples of significant projects designed, managed, or supervised by ACE Moharram Bakhoum:\n\n* [[6th October Bridge]].<ref>{{Citation|title=6th October Bridge|date=2019-09-27|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=6th_October_Bridge&oldid=918292705|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n*[[Cairo Metro|Greater Cairo Metro Lines]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alkhabbar.com/archives/110109|title=\u0645\u062d\u0641\u0648\u0638\" \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0633\u0627\u0639\u062f \u0644\u0644\u0634\u0626\u0648\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u062d\u0632\u0628 \" \u0645\u0633\u062a\u0642\u0628\u0644 \u0648\u0637\u0646 \" \u0648 \"\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0643\u062a\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0634\u0627\u0631\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0631\u0646\u0633\u064a\" \u0634\u0631\u0643\u0629 ( \u0633\u064a\u0633\u062a\u0631\u0627- \u0645\u062d\u0631\u0645 \u2013 \u0628\u0627\u062e\u0648\u0645) \u064a\u0639\u0627\u064a\u0646\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u062f\u062e\u0637 \u0645\u062a\u0631\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0646\u0641\u0627\u0642 \u0625\u0644\u064a \u0642\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0628/\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0628\u0631|last=Ibrahim|first=Samia|website=\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0628\u0631|language=ar|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Cairo Metro|date=2020-02-20|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Cairo_Metro&oldid=941763257|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n* $1-billion road and railway tunnel project under the Suez Canal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canada.constructconnect.com/joc/news/projects/2019/10/sponsored-content-canadian-xypex-water-proofing-product-helps-egypt-to-complete-landmark-tunnel-project-under-suez-canal|title=Sponsored Content: Canadian Xypex water-proofing product helps Egypt to complete landmark tunnel project under Suez Canal - constructconnect.com|date=2019-10-18|website=Journal Of Commerce|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n* Rod el Farag Bridge,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arabcont.com/project-555|title=\u0645\u062d\u0648\u0631 \u0631\u0648\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0631\u062c \"\u0643\u0648\u0628\u0631\u0649 \u062a\u062d\u064a\u0627 \u0645\u0635\u0631\" {{!}} \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0642\u0627\u0648\u0644\u0648\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628|website=arabcont.com|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> which won the Guinness Book of World Records\u2019 certificate for being the world's widest cable-stayed bridge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.middleeastarchitect.com/insight/43125-rod-el-farag-axis-bridge-in-egypt-receives-guinness-world-record-title|title=Rod El-Farag Axis Bridge in Egypt receives Guinness World Record title|website=Middle  East Architect|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n*[[File:Panorma Cairo Stadium.jpg|thumb|Cairo International Stadium|349x349px]][[Luxor International Airport]].\n* [[Cairo International Stadium]].\n* [[Grand Egyptian Museum]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Sphinx float glass factory (1.2 Billion EGP project)[https://eklutdvotyzsri.dailynewssegypt.com/2009/12/21/ace-sees-more-opportunities-in-development/ ACE sees more opportunities in development].\n* Egyptian-German Telecommunication Plant.\n* Egyptian Cement Company Plant.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Engineering companies of Egypt]]\n__INDEX__\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = ACE Moharram Bakhoum\n| logo                = ACE Logo.png\n| type                = [[Privately held company]]\n| industry            = [[Engineering]]\n| founder             = [[Ahmed Moharram]] and [[Michel Bakhoum]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Egypt]]\n| num_locations       = Branches in 12 countries\n| area_served         = Worldwide (100 countries)\n| services            = Engineering and Project Management\n| num_employees       = 2100\n| homepage            = http://www.ace-mb.com/\n}}\n'''ACE Moharram Bakhoum''' is a multi-disciplinary [[engineering]] and [[project management]] consultancy company, based in Egypt.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://eklutdvotyzsri.dailynewssegypt.com/2009/12/21/ace-sees-more-opportunities-in-development/|title=ACE sees more opportunities in development|date=2009-12-21|website=Daily News Egypt|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> ACE Moharram Bakhoum offers services in the fields of planning, engineering design, project management and construction supervision of construction-related activities.\n\n== Operations ==\nThe company operates in 100 countries, with twelve international branch offices working on both private and publicly financed projects.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Market sectors===\nMarket sectors in which the company operates include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ace-consultants.com/services.htm|title=ACE Consulting Engineers - Services|website=www.ace-consultants.com|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n\n* '''Infrastructure for urban development''' \n** Roads network\n** Earthworks and landscape\n** Wastewater, storm drainage\n** Water, irrigation and fire fighting networks\n** Power supply, street lighting, telecom and data networks\n** District cooling networks\n**Water supply and sewerage\n** Water treatment plants\n** Sewerage treatment plants\n** Pumping stations\n** Transmission pipelines\n** Distribution mains\n** Sewers\n* '''Transportation'''\n** Airports\n** Bridges\n** Roads\n** Tunnels\n** Metro / Light rail\n* '''Buildings'''\n** Residential\n** Administration\n** Tourist\n** Commercial\n** Cultural\n** Recreation\n** Healthcare\n** Educational\n** Car parks\n* '''Industrial facilities'''\n** Cement plants\n** Fertilizer plants\n** Power plants\n** Petrochemical plants\n** Other industrial facilities\n* '''Irrigation and Hydraulics'''\n** Dams / Barrages\n** Reservoirs\n** Locks\n\n== History ==\nACE Moharram Bakhoum was established in 1950 as a private partnership between [[Ahmed Moharram]] and [[Michel Bakhoum]]. The first projects executed by the partners was a storage area for printing machines constructed in the basement of a building in Cairo, followed by the design of a pharmacological factory. In the 1950s, the partners made their entry into the field of bridge design, for which they later became widely known. By the 1970s, the company witnessed a regional expansion. In 1970, the first phase of the 6th of October Bridge was opened. This bridge, which is considered the main artery of the Egyptian capital, was the first [[prestressed concrete]] bridge to be entirely designed, constructed and the construction supervised by Egyptian firms - ACE Moharram Bakhoum was the designer and construction supervisor. By this time, ACE had been involved in numerous high-profile projects in Egypt and the Middle East region, and the expansion of its activities to include other disciplines was necessary.\n\n== Significant projects ==\nExamples of significant projects designed, managed, or supervised by ACE Moharram Bakhoum:\n\n* [[6th October Bridge]].<ref>{{Citation|title=6th October Bridge|date=2019-09-27|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=6th_October_Bridge&oldid=918292705|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n* Greater Cairo Metro Lines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alkhabbar.com/archives/110109|title=\u0645\u062d\u0641\u0648\u0638\" \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0633\u0627\u0639\u062f \u0644\u0644\u0634\u0626\u0648\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u062d\u0632\u0628 \" \u0645\u0633\u062a\u0642\u0628\u0644 \u0648\u0637\u0646 \" \u0648 \"\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0643\u062a\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0634\u0627\u0631\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0631\u0646\u0633\u064a\" \u0634\u0631\u0643\u0629 ( \u0633\u064a\u0633\u062a\u0631\u0627- \u0645\u062d\u0631\u0645 \u2013 \u0628\u0627\u062e\u0648\u0645) \u064a\u0639\u0627\u064a\u0646\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u062f\u062e\u0637 \u0645\u062a\u0631\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0646\u0641\u0627\u0642 \u0625\u0644\u064a \u0642\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0628/\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0628\u0631|last=Ibrahim|first=Samia|website=\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0628\u0631|language=ar|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Cairo Metro|date=2020-02-20|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Cairo_Metro&oldid=941763257|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n* $1-billion road and railway tunnel project under the Suez Canal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canada.constructconnect.com/joc/news/projects/2019/10/sponsored-content-canadian-xypex-water-proofing-product-helps-egypt-to-complete-landmark-tunnel-project-under-suez-canal|title=Sponsored Content: Canadian Xypex water-proofing product helps Egypt to complete landmark tunnel project under Suez Canal - constructconnect.com|date=2019-10-18|website=Journal Of Commerce|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n* Rod el Farag Bridge,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arabcont.com/project-555|title=\u0645\u062d\u0648\u0631 \u0631\u0648\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0631\u062c \"\u0643\u0648\u0628\u0631\u0649 \u062a\u062d\u064a\u0627 \u0645\u0635\u0631\" {{!}} \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0642\u0627\u0648\u0644\u0648\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628|website=arabcont.com|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> which won the Guinness Book of World Records\u2019 certificate for being the world's widest cable-stayed bridge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.middleeastarchitect.com/insight/43125-rod-el-farag-axis-bridge-in-egypt-receives-guinness-world-record-title|title=Rod El-Farag Axis Bridge in Egypt receives Guinness World Record title|website=Middle  East Architect|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n*[[File:Panorma Cairo Stadium.jpg|thumb|Cairo International Stadium|349x349px]][[Luxor International Airport]].\n* [[Cairo International Stadium]].\n* [[Grand Egyptian Museum]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Sphinx float glass factory (1.2 Billion EGP project)[https://eklutdvotyzsri.dailynewssegypt.com/2009/12/21/ace-sees-more-opportunities-in-development/ ACE sees more opportunities in development].\n* Egyptian-German Telecommunication Plant.\n* Egyptian Cement Company Plant.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Engineering companies of Egypt]]\n__INDEX__\n", "name_user": "Ibrahimsabotaleb120", "label": "safe", "comment": "edited countries of operation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ACE_Moharram_Bakhoum"}
{"title_page": "\u00c1lvaro Magalh\u00e3es", "text_new": "{{short description|Portuguese football manager and former player}}\n{{For|the writer|\u00c1lvaro Magalh\u00e3es (writer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Portuguese name|Monteiro|Magalh\u00e3es}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name = \u00c1lvaro\n|image =\n|fullname = \u00c1lvaro Monteiro Magalh\u00e3es\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1961|1|3|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Lamego]], Portugal\n|height = 1.80 m\n|position = [[Left back]]\n|currentclub = \n|youthyears1 = 1975\u20131978 | youthclubs1 = Cracks Lamego\n|youthyears2 = 1978\u20131979 | youthclubs2 = [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Acad\u00e9mica de Coimbra \u2013 O.A.F.|Acad\u00e9mica]]\n|years1 = 1979\u20131981 | clubs1 = [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Acad\u00e9mica de Coimbra \u2013 O.A.F.|Acad\u00e9mica]] | caps1 = 56 | goals1 = 1\n|years2 = 1981\u20131990 | clubs2 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] | caps2 = 177 | goals2 = 6\n|years3 = 1990\u20131991 | clubs3 = [[C.F. Estrela da Amadora|Estrela Amadora]] | caps3 = 19 | goals3 = 0\n|years4 = 1991\u20131993 | clubs4 = [[Leix\u00f5es S.C.|Leix\u00f5es]] | caps4 = 41 | goals4 = 0\n|totalcaps = 293 | totalgoals = 7\n|nationalyears1 = 1981\u20131988 | nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] | nationalcaps1 = 20 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n|manageryears1 = 1994\u20131997 | managerclubs1 = [[Lusit\u00e2nia F.C.|Lourosa]]\n|manageryears2 = 1997\u20131998 | managerclubs2 = [[C.D. Santa Clara|Santa Clara]]\n|manageryears3 = 1998 | managerclubs3 = [[G.D. Chaves|Chaves]]\n|manageryears4 = 1998\u20132000 | managerclubs4 = [[Gil Vicente F.C.|Gil Vicente]]\n|manageryears5 = 2000\u20132001 | managerclubs5 = [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Guimar\u00e3es]]\n|manageryears6 = 2001\u20132002 | managerclubs6 = [[C.F. Estrela da Amadora|Estrela Amadora]]\n|manageryears7 = 2002\u20132003 | managerclubs7 = [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Naval 1\u00ba de Maio|Naval]]\n|manageryears8 = 2003\u20132005 | managerclubs8 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] (assistant)\n|manageryears9 = 2005\u20132006 | managerclubs9 = [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Naval 1\u00ba de Maio|Naval]]\n|manageryears10 = 2006\u20132008 | managerclubs10 = [[S.C. Olhanense|Olhanense]]\n|manageryears11 = 2008 | managerclubs11 = [[C.D. Feirense|Feirense]]\n|manageryears12 = 2008 | managerclubs12 = [[FC Gloria Buz\u0103u|Gloria Buz\u0103u]]\n|manageryears13 = 2009\u20132011 | managerclubs13 = [[G.D. Interclube|Interclube]]\n|manageryears14 = 2012 | managerclubs14 = [[Clube Nacional de Benguela|Nacional Benguela]]\n|manageryears15 = 2012\u20132013 | managerclubs15 = [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Naval 1\u00ba de Maio|Naval]]\n|manageryears16 = 2013\u20132014 | managerclubs16 = [[C.D. Tondela|Tondela]]\n|manageryears17 = 2016\u20132017 | managerclubs17 = [[Gil Vicente F.C.|Gil Vicente]]\n|manageryears18 = 2019  | managerclubs18 = [[S.C. Farense|Farense]]\n|medaltemplates = {{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{medal|Country|{{fb|POR}}}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[UEFA European Championship]]|}}\n{{Medal|B|[[UEFA Euro 1984|1984 France]]|}}\n}}\n'''\u00c1lvaro Monteiro Magalh\u00e3es''' (born 3 January 1961), known simply as '''\u00c1lvaro''', is a Portuguese former [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[left back]], and a current [[Manager (association football)|manager]].\n\nHe amassed [[Primeira Liga]] totals of 224 matches and six goals over 11 seasons, mainly with [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] with which he spent nine years, winning ten major titles.\n\n\u00c1lvaro represented [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] at the [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986 World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 1984|Euro 1984]]. In 1994, he began working as a coach.\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Lamego]], \u00c1lvaro made his [[Primeira Liga]] debut in 1980 with [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Acad\u00e9mica de Coimbra \u2013 O.A.F.|Acad\u00e9mica de Coimbra]], moving subsequently to [[S.L. Benfica]]. After two seasons he became first-choice, helping the [[Lisbon]] club to four leagues and as many [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|domestic cups]] (three consecutive in the latter competition) while amassing more than 200 official appearances.<ref>{{cite book|last=Malheiro|first=Jo\u00e3o|title=Memorial Benfica 100 Gl\u00f3rias|trans-title=Benfica Memorial, 100 glories|date=July 2006|publisher=QuidNovi|isbn=978-972-8998-26-4|edition=Third|page=15|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1990, after only 13 games in his last two seasons combined \u2013 Benfica also appeared in two [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] finals during that timeframe, but he was only a fringe player \u2013 \u00c1lvaro left and signed with neighbours [[C.F. Estrela da Amadora]], helping the team to [[1990\u201391 European Cup Winners' Cup|the second round]] of the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]]; however, [[1990\u201391 Primeira Liga|the league ended in relegation]]. He closed out his career at the age of 32 in the [[Segunda Liga|second division]], with [[Leix\u00f5es S.C.|Leix\u00f5es SC]].\n\nOne year after retiring, \u00c1lvaro began a coaching career, working with several first and second level teams, his first experience in the former tier being with [[G.D. Chaves]] in [[1997\u201398 Primeira Liga|1997\u201398]], narrowly avoiding relegation.\n\nFrom 2003 to 2005, he was assistant manager at Benfica under [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Camacho]] and [[Giovanni Trapattoni]] respectively, winning the league title in [[2004\u201305 Primeira Liga|the second season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cmjornal.pt/desporto/detalhe/fui-eu-que-fiz-trapattoni-campeao|title=\"Fui eu que fiz Trapattoni campe\u00e3o\"|trans-title=\"I made Trapattoni champion\"|newspaper=[[Correio da Manh\u00e3]]|language=Portuguese|date=24 April 2010|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> In the latter years of the decade he had spells in [[Romania]] and [[Angola]], being [[Girabola]] champion in the latter country with [[G.D. Interclube]], the second time in the [[Luanda]] club's history.<ref name=GIRABOLA>{{cite news|url=https://www.dn.pt/desporto/futebol-internacional/interior/alvaro-magalhaes-campeao-de-angola-1699882.html|title=\u00c1lvaro Magalh\u00e3es campe\u00e3o de Angola|trans-title=\u00c1lvaro Magalh\u00e3es Angolan champion|newspaper=[[Di\u00e1rio de Not\u00edcias]]|language=Portuguese|date=31 October 2010|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, Magalh\u00e3es penned a new two-year contract but, on 29 March 2011, he was relieved of his duties.<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201103290625.html Angola: Interclube rescind contract with Portuguese coach]; All Africa, 29 March 2011</ref> In early February 2012, he appointed coach of fellow league side [[Clube Nacional de Benguela]];<ref>[http://www.portalangop.co.ao/motix/en_us/noticias/desporto/2012/1/5/National-Benguela-presents-new-coach,5d4d9271-67de-46a3-a9b9-a0deaccff3a2.html National de Benguela presents new coach]; [[Angola Press News Agency]], 2 February 2012</ref> shortly after, however, he returned to his country, signing with [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Naval 1\u00ba de Maio]] which he had already managed in [[2005\u201306 Primeira Liga|2005\u201306's top flight]] and [[2002\u201303 Segunda Liga|2002\u201303's division two]].\n\n==International career==\n\u00c1lvaro was [[Cap (sport)|capped]] 20 times for [[Portuguese national football team|Portugal]], his debut coming on 16 December 1981 in a 2\u20135 defeat with [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]], a [[Exhibition game|friendly match]]. He was picked for the squads present at the [[UEFA Euro 1984]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pt.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1984/matches/round=203/match=3461/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Platini faz a diferen\u00e7a em meia-final de sonho|trans-title=Platini makes the difference in dream semi-final|publisher=UEFA|language=Portuguese|date=4 October 2003|accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> and the [[1986 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{FIFA player|166525}}</ref>\n\nAfter the infamous [[Saltillo Affair]] in the latter tournament, \u00c1lvaro was one of the few players that did not defect from the national team, and his last international appearance came on 16 November 1988 in a 1\u20130 win against [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] for the [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990 World Cup]] [[1990 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualifiers]], in [[Porto]].\n\n==Personal life==\nMagalh\u00e3es was born with [[polydactylism]] in his left hand, and was [[nickname]]d ''Seis dedos'' (six fingers) due to this condition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dn.pt/desporto/futebol-internacional/interior/casos-semelhantes-em-portugal-1425653.html|title=Casos semelhantes em Portugal|trans-title=Similar cases in Portugal|newspaper=Di\u00e1rio de Not\u00edcias|language=Portuguese|date=20 November 2009|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''Benfica'''\n*[[Primeira Liga]]: 1982\u201383, 1983\u201384, 1986\u201387, 1988\u201389<ref>{{cite magazine|date=April\u2013June 2017|title=Especial 'Tetra'|trans-title='Tetra' special edition|language=Portuguese|magazine=M\u00edstica|location=Portugal|publisher=[[Impresa]]|issue=33|page=92|issn=3846-0823}}</ref>\n*[[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]]:<ref name=\"bi\">{{cite magazine|date=May 2015|title=Bicampe\u00f5es para a hist\u00f3ria|trans-title=Back-to-back champions for the ages|language=Portuguese|magazine=[[Vis\u00e3o]]|location=Portugal|publisher=Impresa|page=56|issn=0872-3540}}</ref> 1982\u201383, 1984\u201385, 1985\u201386, 1986\u201387\n*[[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]]:<ref name=\"bi\"/> 1985, 1989\n*[[Ta\u00e7a de Honra]] (1)<ref name=\"bi\"/>\n*[[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]]: Runner-up 1987\u201388, 1989\u201390\n*[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]: Runner-up 1982\u201383\n\n===Manager===\n'''Interclube'''\n*[[Girabola]]: [[2010 Girabola|2010]]<ref name=GIRABOLA/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n*{{ForaDeJogo manager}}\n*{{NFT player}}\n*[https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=400 Portugal stats at Eu-Football]\n\n{{Portugal Squad 1984 Euro Cup}}\n{{Portugal Squad 1986 World Cup}}\n{{Gil Vicente F.C. managers}}\n{{Vit\u00f3ria S.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alvaro Magalhaes}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lamego]]\n[[Category:Portuguese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:LigaPro players]]\n[[Category:Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Acad\u00e9mica de Coimbra \u2013 O.A.F. players]]\n[[Category:S.L. Benfica footballers]]\n[[Category:C.F. Estrela da Amadora players]]\n[[Category:Leix\u00f5es S.C. players]]\n[[Category:Portugal international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1984 players]]\n[[Category:1986 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese football managers]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga managers]]\n[[Category:LigaPro managers]]\n[[Category:C.D. Santa Clara managers]]\n[[Category:G.D. Chaves managers]]\n[[Category:Gil Vicente F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Vit\u00f3ria S.C. managers]]\n[[Category:C.F. Estrela da Amadora managers]]\n[[Category:Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Naval 1\u00ba de Maio managers]]\n[[Category:S.C. Olhanense managers]]\n[[Category:C.D. Feirense managers]]\n[[Category:C.D. Tondela managers]]\n[[Category:S.C. Farense managers]]\n[[Category:Liga I managers]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Romania]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Angola]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Romania]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Angola]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Portuguese football manager and former player}}\n{{For|the writer|\u00c1lvaro Magalh\u00e3es (writer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Portuguese name|Monteiro|Magalh\u00e3es}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name = \u00c1lvaro\n|image =\n|fullname = \u00c1lvaro Monteiro Magalh\u00e3es\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1961|1|3|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Lamego]], Portugal\n|height = 1.80 m\n|position = [[Left back]]\n|currentclub = \n|youthyears1 = 1975\u20131978 | youthclubs1 = Cracks Lamego\n|youthyears2 = 1978\u20131979 | youthclubs2 = [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Acad\u00e9mica de Coimbra \u2013 O.A.F.|Acad\u00e9mica]]\n|years1 = 1979\u20131981 | clubs1 = [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Acad\u00e9mica de Coimbra \u2013 O.A.F.|Acad\u00e9mica]] | caps1 = 56 | goals1 = 1\n|years2 = 1981\u20131990 | clubs2 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] | caps2 = 177 | goals2 = 6\n|years3 = 1990\u20131991 | clubs3 = [[C.F. Estrela da Amadora|Estrela Amadora]] | caps3 = 19 | goals3 = 0\n|years4 = 1991\u20131993 | clubs4 = [[Leix\u00f5es S.C.|Leix\u00f5es]] | caps4 = 41 | goals4 = 0\n|totalcaps = 293 | totalgoals = 7\n|nationalyears1 = 1981\u20131988 | nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] | nationalcaps1 = 20 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n|manageryears1 = 1994\u20131997 | managerclubs1 = [[Lusit\u00e2nia F.C.|Lourosa]]\n|manageryears2 = 1997\u20131998 | managerclubs2 = [[C.D. Santa Clara|Santa Clara]]\n|manageryears3 = 1998 | managerclubs3 = [[G.D. Chaves|Chaves]]\n|manageryears4 = 1998\u20132000 | managerclubs4 = [[Gil Vicente F.C.|Gil Vicente]]\n|manageryears5 = 2000\u20132001 | managerclubs5 = [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Guimar\u00e3es]]\n|manageryears6 = 2001\u20132002 | managerclubs6 = [[C.F. Estrela da Amadora|Estrela Amadora]]\n|manageryears7 = 2002\u20132003 | managerclubs7 = [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Naval 1\u00ba de Maio|Naval]]\n|manageryears8 = 2003\u20132005 | managerclubs8 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] (assistant)\n|manageryears9 = 2005\u20132006 | managerclubs9 = [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Naval 1\u00ba de Maio|Naval]]\n|manageryears10 = 2006\u20132008 | managerclubs10 = [[S.C. Olhanense|Olhanense]]\n|manageryears11 = 2008 | managerclubs11 = [[C.D. Feirense|Feirense]]\n|manageryears12 = 2008 | managerclubs12 = [[FC Gloria Buz\u0103u|Gloria Buz\u0103u]]\n|manageryears13 = 2009\u20132011 | managerclubs13 = [[G.D. Interclube|Interclube]]\n|manageryears14 = 2012 | managerclubs14 = [[Clube Nacional de Benguela|Nacional Benguela]]\n|manageryears15 = 2012\u20132013 | managerclubs15 = [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Naval 1\u00ba de Maio|Naval]]\n|manageryears16 = 2013\u20132014 | managerclubs16 = [[C.D. Tondela|Tondela]]\n|manageryears17 = 2016\u20132017 | managerclubs17 = [[Gil Vicente F.C.|Gil Vicente]]\n|manageryears18 = 2019  | managerclubs18 = [[S.C. Farense|Farense]]\n|medaltemplates = {{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{medal|Country|{{fb|POR}}}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[UEFA European Championship]]|}}\n{{Medal|B|[[UEFA Euro 1984|1984 France]]|}}\n}}\n'''\u00c1lvaro Monteiro Magalh\u00e3es''' (born 3 January 1961), known simply as '''\u00c1lvaro''', is a Portuguese former [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[left back]], and a current [[Manager (association football)|manager]].\n\nHe amassed [[Primeira Liga]] totals of 224 matches and six goals over 11 seasons, mainly with [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] with which he spent nine years, winning ten major titles.\n\n\u00c1lvaro represented [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] at the [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986 World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 1984|Euro 1984]]. In 1994, he began working as a coach.\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Lamego]], \u00c1lvaro made his [[Primeira Liga]] debuts in 1980 with [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Acad\u00e9mica de Coimbra \u2013 O.A.F.|Acad\u00e9mica de Coimbra]], moving subsequently to [[S.L. Benfica]]. After two seasons he became first-choice, helping the [[Lisbon]] club to four leagues and as many [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|domestic cups]] (three consecutive in the latter competition) while amassing more than 200 official appearances.<ref>{{cite book|last=Malheiro|first=Jo\u00e3o|title=Memorial Benfica 100 Gl\u00f3rias|trans-title=Benfica Memorial, 100 glories|date=July 2006|publisher=QuidNovi|isbn=978-972-8998-26-4|edition=Third|page=15|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1990, after only 13 games in his last two seasons combined \u2013 Benfica also appeared in two [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] finals during that timeframe, but he was only a fringe player \u2013 \u00c1lvaro left and signed with neighbours [[C.F. Estrela da Amadora]], helping the team to [[1990\u201391 European Cup Winners' Cup|the second round]] of the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]]; however, [[1990\u201391 Primeira Liga|the league ended in relegation]]. He closed out his career at the age of 32 in the [[Segunda Liga|second division]], with [[Leix\u00f5es S.C.|Leix\u00f5es SC]].\n\nOne year after retiring, \u00c1lvaro began a coaching career, working with several first and second level teams, his first experience in the former tier being with [[G.D. Chaves]] in [[1997\u201398 Primeira Liga|1997\u201398]], narrowly avoiding relegation.\n\nFrom 2003 to 2005, he was assistant manager at Benfica under [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Camacho]] and [[Giovanni Trapattoni]] respectively, winning the league title in [[2004\u201305 Primeira Liga|the second season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cmjornal.pt/desporto/detalhe/fui-eu-que-fiz-trapattoni-campeao|title=\"Fui eu que fiz Trapattoni campe\u00e3o\"|trans-title=\"I made Trapattoni champion\"|newspaper=[[Correio da Manh\u00e3]]|language=Portuguese|date=24 April 2010|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> In the latter years of the decade he had spells in [[Romania]] and [[Angola]], being [[Girabola]] champion in the latter country with [[G.D. Interclube]], the second time in the [[Luanda]] club's history.<ref name=GIRABOLA>{{cite news|url=https://www.dn.pt/desporto/futebol-internacional/interior/alvaro-magalhaes-campeao-de-angola-1699882.html|title=\u00c1lvaro Magalh\u00e3es campe\u00e3o de Angola|trans-title=\u00c1lvaro Magalh\u00e3es Angolan champion|newspaper=[[Di\u00e1rio de Not\u00edcias]]|language=Portuguese|date=31 October 2010|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, Magalh\u00e3es penned a new two-year contract but, on 29 March 2011, he was relieved of his duties.<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201103290625.html Angola: Interclube rescind contract with Portuguese coach]; All Africa, 29 March 2011</ref> In early February 2012, he appointed coach of fellow league side [[Clube Nacional de Benguela]];<ref>[http://www.portalangop.co.ao/motix/en_us/noticias/desporto/2012/1/5/National-Benguela-presents-new-coach,5d4d9271-67de-46a3-a9b9-a0deaccff3a2.html National de Benguela presents new coach]; [[Angola Press News Agency]], 2 February 2012</ref> shortly after, however, he returned to his country, signing with [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Naval 1\u00ba de Maio]] which he had already managed in [[2005\u201306 Primeira Liga|2005\u201306's top flight]] and [[2002\u201303 Segunda Liga|2002\u201303's division two]].\n\n==International career==\n\u00c1lvaro was [[Cap (sport)|capped]] 20 times for [[Portuguese national football team|Portugal]], his debut coming on 16 December 1981 in a 2\u20135 defeat with [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]], a [[Exhibition game|friendly match]]. He was picked for the squads present at the [[UEFA Euro 1984]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pt.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1984/matches/round=203/match=3461/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Platini faz a diferen\u00e7a em meia-final de sonho|trans-title=Platini makes the difference in dream semi-final|publisher=UEFA|language=Portuguese|date=4 October 2003|accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> and the [[1986 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{FIFA player|166525}}</ref>\n\nAfter the infamous [[Saltillo Affair]] in the latter tournament, \u00c1lvaro was one of the few players that did not defect from the national team, and his last international appearance came on 16 November 1988 in a 1\u20130 win against [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] for the [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990 World Cup]] [[1990 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualifiers]], in [[Porto]].\n\n==Personal life==\nMagalh\u00e3es was born with [[polydactylism]] in his left hand, and was [[nickname]]d ''Seis dedos'' (six fingers) due to this condition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dn.pt/desporto/futebol-internacional/interior/casos-semelhantes-em-portugal-1425653.html|title=Casos semelhantes em Portugal|trans-title=Similar cases in Portugal|newspaper=Di\u00e1rio de Not\u00edcias|language=Portuguese|date=20 November 2009|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''Benfica'''\n*[[Primeira Liga]]: 1982\u201383, 1983\u201384, 1986\u201387, 1988\u201389<ref>{{cite magazine|date=April\u2013June 2017|title=Especial 'Tetra'|trans-title='Tetra' special edition|language=Portuguese|magazine=M\u00edstica|location=Portugal|publisher=[[Impresa]] Publishing|issue=33|page=92|issn=3846-0823}}</ref>\n*[[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]]:<ref name=\"bi\">{{cite magazine|date=May 2015|title=Bicampe\u00f5es para a hist\u00f3ria|trans-title=Back-to-back champions for the ages|language=Portuguese|magazine=[[Vis\u00e3o]]|location=Portugal|publisher=[[Impresa]] Publishing|page=56|issn=0872-3540}}</ref> 1982\u201383, 1984\u201385, 1985\u201386, 1986\u201387\n*[[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]]:<ref name=\"bi\"/> 1985, 1989\n*[[Ta\u00e7a de Honra]] (1)<ref name=\"bi\"/>\n*[[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]]: Runner-up 1987\u201388, 1989\u201390\n*[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]: Runner-up 1982\u201383\n\n===Manager===\n'''Interclube'''\n*[[Girabola]]: [[2010 Girabola|2010]]<ref name=GIRABOLA/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n*{{ForaDeJogo manager}}\n*{{NFT player}}\n*[https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=400 Portugal stats at Eu-Football]\n\n{{Portugal Squad 1984 Euro Cup}}\n{{Portugal Squad 1986 World Cup}}\n{{Gil Vicente F.C. managers}}\n{{Vit\u00f3ria S.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alvaro Magalhaes}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lamego]]\n[[Category:Portuguese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:LigaPro players]]\n[[Category:Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Acad\u00e9mica de Coimbra \u2013 O.A.F. players]]\n[[Category:S.L. Benfica footballers]]\n[[Category:C.F. Estrela da Amadora players]]\n[[Category:Leix\u00f5es S.C. players]]\n[[Category:Portugal international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1984 players]]\n[[Category:1986 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese football managers]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga managers]]\n[[Category:LigaPro managers]]\n[[Category:C.D. Santa Clara managers]]\n[[Category:G.D. Chaves managers]]\n[[Category:Gil Vicente F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Vit\u00f3ria S.C. managers]]\n[[Category:C.F. Estrela da Amadora managers]]\n[[Category:Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Naval 1\u00ba de Maio managers]]\n[[Category:S.C. Olhanense managers]]\n[[Category:C.D. Feirense managers]]\n[[Category:C.D. Tondela managers]]\n[[Category:S.C. Farense managers]]\n[[Category:Liga I managers]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Romania]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Angola]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Romania]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Angola]]\n", "name_user": "Quite A Character", "label": "safe", "comment": "Ditto (please read my last summary).", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%81lvaro_Magalh%C3%A3es"}
