anies based in Mainz]]\n[[Category:German companies established in 2016]]\n[[Category:German-language television stations]]\n[[Category:German television networks]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2016]]\n[[Category:Internet television streaming services]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 2016]]\n[[Category:Media in Mainz]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Mainz]]\n[[Category:Publicly funded broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Subscription video on demand services]]\n[[Category:S\u00fcdwestrundfunk]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Germany]]\n[[Category:ZDF]]\n", "name_user": "Wikiolo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Funk_(streaming_service)"}
{"title_page": "ZC3H11B", "text_new": "'''ZC3H11B''' \n\nZinc finger CCCH-type containing protein 11B is a [[protein]] in humans that is encoded by the ZC3H11B [[gene]] <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/|title=Home - Gene - NCBI|website=www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. The zc3h11b gene is located on [[chromosome 1]], on the long arm, in band 4 section 1. This protein is also known as ZC3HDC11B. The zc3h11b gene is a total of 5,134 base pairs long, and the protein is 805 amino acids in length. The zc3h11b gene has 2 [[Exon|exons]] in total.\n\n<br />\n\n==== '''Clinical Significance''' ====\nCurrent research has identified ZC3H11B as [[Single-nucleotide polymorphism|single-nucleotide polymorphisms]] (SNPs) that are the most common genetic variation among groups with high [[Near-sightedness|myopia]] and corneal [[astigmatism]] <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Fan|first=Qiao|last2=Barathi|first2=Veluchamy A.|last3=Cheng|first3=Ching-Yu|last4=Zhou|first4=Xin|last5=Meguro|first5=Akira|last6=Nakata|first6=Isao|last7=Khor|first7=Chiea-Chuen|last8=Goh|first8=Liang-Kee|last9=Li|first9=Yi-Ju|last10=Lim|first10=Wan'e|last11=Ho|first11=Candice E. H.|date=2012|title=Genetic variants on chromosome 1q41 influence ocular axial length and high myopia|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22685421|journal=PLoS genetics|volume=8|issue=6|pages=e1002753|doi=10.1371/journal.pgen.1002753|issn=1553-7404|pmc=3369958|pmid=22685421}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Shah|first=Rupal L.|last2=Guggenheim|first2=Jeremy A.|last3=UK Biobank Eye and Vision Consortium|date=2018-12-01|title=Genome-wide association studies for corneal and refractive astigmatism in UK Biobank demonstrate a shared role for myopia susceptibility loci|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s00439-018-1942-8|journal=Human Genetics|language=en|volume=137|issue=11|pages=881\u2013896|doi=10.1007/s00439-018-1942-8|issn=1432-1203|pmc=PMC6267700|pmid=30306274}}</ref>. As of April 2020, there have been no other published association studies linking ZC3H11B with other conditions.\n<br />\n\n===== Myopia =====\nMyopia, also known as shortsightedness or nearsightedness, is a condition caused by a [[refractive error]] in which the shape of the eye is either elongated or the cornea is too curved <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aoa.org/patients-and-public/eye-and-vision-problems/glossary-of-eye-and-vision-conditions/myopia|title=Myopia (Nearsightedness)|website=www.aoa.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. In developed countries, this condition occurs in over 50% of the population with a high rate of occurrence among adults (80-90%) in East Asia and occurs approximately in 30% of the population in the United States <ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wu|first=Pei-Chang|last2=Huang|first2=Hsiu-Mei|last3=Yu|first3=Hun-Ju|last4=Fang|first4=Po-Chiung|last5=Chen|first5=Chueh-Tan|date=2016|title=Epidemiology of Myopia|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27898441|journal=Asia-Pacific Journal of Ophthalmology (Philadelphia, Pa.)|volume=5|issue=6|pages=386\u2013393|doi=10.1097/APO.0000000000000236|issn=2162-0989|pmid=27898441|via=}}</ref>.\n\nMyopia is categorized in two groups. The first of which comprises of people with low to medium amount of myopia, or simple myopia, and is diagnosed at 0 to -6 [[Dioptre|diopters]] and is treated with corrective lenses. The second is classified as high myopia and is diagnosed at greater than -6 diopters and typically are found in cases of [[retinal detachment]], [[macular degeneration]], and [[glaucoma]] <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fredrick|first=Douglas R|date=2002-05-18|title=Myopia|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1123161/|journal=BMJ : British Medical Journal|volume=324|issue=7347|pages=1195\u20131199|issn=0959-8138|pmc=1123161|pmid=12016188}}</ref>. \u00a0Myopia is considered as one of the leading causes of blindness and visual impairment in the world by the [[World Health Organization]] <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pararajasegaram|first=R.|date=1999|title=VISION 2020-the right to sight: from strategies to action|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10511033|journal=American Journal of Ophthalmology|volume=128|issue=3|pages=359\u2013360|doi=10.1016/s0002-9394(99)00251-2|issn=0002-9394|pmid=10511033|via=}}</ref>.\n\nAn elongated ocular [[Intraocular lens power calculation|axial length]] (AL), or distance from the anterior corneal surface to the [[retinal pigment epithelium]] <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bhardwaj|first=Veena|last2=Rajeshbhai|first2=Gandhi Parth|date=2013|title=Axial Length, Anterior Chamber Depth-A Study in Different Age Groups and Refractive Errors|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3843406/|journal=Journal of Clinical and Diagnostic Research : JCDR|volume=7|issue=10|pages=2211\u20132212|doi=10.7860/JCDR/2013/7015.3473|issn=2249-782X|pmc=3843406|pmid=24298478|via=}}</ref>, is a determinant of the development of myopia. A [[genome-wide association study]] conducted in a population of Chinese adults and children as well as Malay adults identified that ZC3H11B is associated with AL and high myopia <ref name=\":1\" />. There were ZC3H11B [[Messenger RNA|mRNA]] expression levels in the brain, placenta, neural retina, [[Retinal pigment epithelium|retina pigment epithelium]], and [[sclera]] with a greater decrease in quantity or [[Downregulation and upregulation|down-regulated]] expression levels in myopic eyes than non-myopic eyes. This identification was confirmed in another genome-wide association study along with the identification of additional significant [[Locus (genetics)|loci]] for AL of [[R-spondin 1|RSPO1]] (involved in [[Wnt signaling pathway|Wnt signaling]] or regulation of eyeball size), [[C3orf62|C3orf26]], ZNRF3 (involved in Wnt signaling), and [[ALPPL2]] <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cheng|first=Ching-Yu|last2=Schache|first2=Maria|last3=Ikram|first3=M.\u00a0Kamran|last4=Young|first4=Terri\u00a0L.|last5=Guggenheim|first5=Jeremy\u00a0A.|last6=Vitart|first6=Veronique|last7=MacGregor|first7=Stuart|last8=Verhoeven|first8=Virginie\u00a0J.M.|last9=Barathi|first9=Veluchamy\u00a0A.|last10=Liao|first10=Jiemin|last11=Hysi|first11=Pirro\u00a0G.|date=2013-08-08|title=Nine Loci for Ocular Axial Length Identified through Genome-wide Association Studies, Including Shared Loci with Refractive Error|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3772747/|journal=American Journal of Human Genetics|volume=93|issue=2|pages=264\u2013277|doi=10.1016/j.ajhg.2013.06.016|issn=0002-9297|pmc=3772747|pmid=24144296}}</ref>. Thus, this identification of shared association AL genes indicates that AL and refraction may be caused by different optic pathways. Additionally, a genome-wide association study in Chinese populations confirmed that ZC3H11B is a susceptibility gene for the development of high and extreme myopia <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tang|first=Shu Min|last2=Li|first2=Fen Fen|last3=Lu|first3=Shi Yao|last4=Kam|first4=Ka Wai|last5=Tam|first5=Pancy O. S.|last6=Tham|first6=Clement C.|last7=Pang|first7=Chi Pui|last8=Yam|first8=Jason C. S.|last9=Chen|first9=Li Jia|date=2019-07-12|title=Association of the ZC3H11B, ZFHX1B and SNTB1 genes with myopia of different severities|url=https://bjo.bmj.com/content/early/2019/07/12/bjophthalmol-2019-314203|journal=British Journal of Ophthalmology|language=en|doi=10.1136/bjophthalmol-2019-314203|issn=0007-1161|pmid=31300455}}</ref>.\n<br />\n\n===== Astigmatism =====\nAn astigmatism is a condition in which the curvature of the [[cornea]] or [[Lens (anatomy)|lens]] is abnormal <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aao.org/eye-health/diseases/what-is-astigmatism|title=What Is Astigmatism?|date=2018-08-31|website=American Academy of Ophthalmology|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. Astigmatisms can be classified as corneal astigmatism in which the corneal shape is irregular, lenticular astigmatism in which the lens shape is irregular, or refractive astigmatism. Astigmatism is typically treated with corrective lenses or surgery (such as [[LASIK]]) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.health.harvard.edu/a_to_z/astigmatism-a-to-z|title=Astigmatism|last=Publishing|first=Harvard Health|website=Harvard Health|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\nRefractive and corneal astigmatism may lead to the development of [[amblyopia]], or lazy eye, if left untreated. A genome-wide association study of individuals of European ancestry identified the ZC3H11B gene as significant for corneal astigmatism <ref name=\":2\" />. Additionally, there were two other loci were identified to demonstrate genome-wide significant association for corneal astigmatism, [[E3 ubiquitin ligase HERC2|HERC2]] and TSPAN10/[[NPLOC4]].\n<br />\n\n==== '''Protein''' ====\n\n===== Conserved Domains =====\nThe ZC3H11B protein has three [[Protein domain|conserved domains]]. These include [[zinc finger]] domains, which are one of the most common or abundant protein groups often involved in regulation of cellular processes <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cassandri|first=Matteo|last2=Smirnov|first2=Artem|last3=Novelli|first3=Flavia|last4=Pitolli|first4=Consuelo|last5=Agostini|first5=Massimiliano|last6=Malewicz|first6=Michal|last7=Melino|first7=Gerry|last8=Raschell\u00e0|first8=Giuseppe|date=2017-11-13|title=Zinc-finger proteins in health and disease|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/cddiscovery201771|journal=Cell Death Discovery|language=en|volume=3|issue=1|pages=1\u201312|doi=10.1038/cddiscovery.2017.71|issn=2058-7716}}</ref>, and [[coiled coil]] domains, which are a structurally conserved protien group present in all domains of life often involved in molecular spacing, [[Vesicle (biology and chemistry)|vesicle]] tethering, and [[DNA]] recognition and cleavage <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Truebestein|first=Linda|last2=Leonard|first2=Thomas A.|date=2016|title=Coiled\u2010coils: The long and short of it|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5082667/|journal=Bioessays|volume=38|issue=9|pages=903\u2013916|doi=10.1002/bies.201600062|issn=0265-9247|pmc=5082667|pmid=27492088|via=}}</ref>. Both the zinc finger and coiled coil domains are [[Conserved sequence|conserved]] in [[Eukaryote|eukaryotes]].\n\nZinc finger C3H1-type 1 is located from [[Amino acid|amino acids]] 2-29 ,and zinc finger C3H1-type 2 is located from amino acids 31-57 <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/A0A1B0GTU1|title=UniProtKB - A0A1B0GTU1 (ZC11B_HUMAN)|last=|first=|date=|website=UniProt|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. Zinc finger C3H1-type proteins have been identifed to interact with 3' region of untranslated [[Messenger RNA|mRNAs]] <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hall|first=Traci M Tanaka|date=2005-06-01|title=Multiple modes of RNA recognition by zinc finger proteins|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0959440X05000837|journal=Current Opinion in Structural Biology|series=Sequences and topology/Nucleic acids|language=en|volume=15|issue=3|pages=367\u2013373|doi=10.1016/j.sbi.2005.04.004|issn=0959-440X}}</ref>. Coiled coil is located from positions 403-423 amino acids of the protein <ref name=\":4\" /> .\n<br />\n\n===== Secondary Structure =====\nCurrently the [[Secondary structure of proteins|secondary structure]] of ZC3H11B is unknown. \n\nThe predicted secondary structure of ZC3H11B is a [[Protein structure prediction|loop]] secondary structure composition <ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://open.predictprotein.org/|title=PredictProtein|last=|first=|date=|website=PredictProtein|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, which are irregular secondary structures that connect two secondary structural elements and are able to change the direction of [[Peptide|polypeptide chain]] propagation <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dhar|first=Jesmita|last2=Chakrabarti|first2=Pinak|date=2015-06-01|title=Defining the loop structures in proteins based on composite \u03b2-turn mimics|url=https://academic.oup.com/peds/article/28/6/153/1445671|journal=Protein Engineering, Design and Selection|language=en|volume=28|issue=6|pages=153\u2013161|doi=10.1093/protein/gzv017|issn=1741-0126}}</ref>.  The loop is predicted to be exposed for [[Protein\u2013protein interaction|binding]] <ref name=\":5\" />.\n\n===== [[Post-translational modification|Post-Translational Modification]] =====\nZC3H11B is likely found in the nucleus <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psort.hgc.jp/form2.html|title=PSORT II Prediction|website=psort.hgc.jp|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. ZC3H11B is predicted to undergo various [[Protein phosphorylation|phosphorylations]], [[O-GlcNAcylations]], [[Glycation|glycations]], and [[O-linked glycosylation|O-glycosylations]] <ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbs.dtu.dk/services/|title=CBS Prediction Servers|website=www.cbs.dtu.dk|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\nExample of sites predicted for phosphorylation, a mechanism in which a [[phosphoryl group]] is added and important in biological regulation and other cellular processes <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nestler|first=Eric J.|last2=Greengard|first2=Paul|date=1999|title=Protein Phosphorylation is of Fundamental Importance in Biological Regulation|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK28063/|journal=Basic Neurochemistry: Molecular, Cellular and Medical Aspects. 6th edition|language=en}}</ref>, occur on 108, 149, 196,229, 290, and 330 <ref name=\":6\" />. Example of sites predicted for O-GlcNAcylations, a mechanism in which a [[Protein O-GlcNAc transferase|O-linked N-acetylglucosamine]] (O-GlcNAc) is added and important for regulation of cellular processes <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Xiaoyong|last2=Qian|first2=Kevin|date=2017|title=Protein O-GlcNAcylation: emerging mechanisms and functions|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28488703|journal=Nature Reviews. Molecular Cell Biology|volume=18|issue=7|pages=452\u2013465|doi=10.1038/nrm.2017.22|issn=1471-0080|pmc=5667541|pmid=28488703|via=}}</ref>, are 488, 744, and 732 <ref name=\":6\" />. Examples of sites predicted for glycations, a mechanism in which [[glucose]] binds with proteins and [[Lipid|lipids]], are 140, 359, 669, and 776 <ref name=\":6\" />. Example of sites predicted for O-glycosylation , a mechanism in which sugars or[[Monosaccharide|monosaccharides]] add to [[Hydroxy group|hydroxyl groups]] of proteins <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/biochemistry-genetics-and-molecular-biology/o-linked-glycosylation|title=O-Linked Glycosylation - an overview {{!}} ScienceDirect Topics|website=www.sciencedirect.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>, occur on 179 and 386 <ref name=\":6\" />.\n<br />\n\n==== '''Function''' ====\nThe ZC3H11B protein is expressed in various tissues including those of the [[Testicle|testis]], heart, leg, and [[Adrenal gland|adrenal]] <ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://monarchinitiative.org/gene/HGNC:25659#anatomy|title=Monarch Initiative Explorer|website=monarchinitiative.org|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. ZC3H11B is predicted to be involved in [[Metal-binding protein|metal ion binding]], a mechanism that involves combination of a [[Metal|metal ion]] or [[chelation]], as inferred from Electronic Association <ref name=\":0\" />.\n<br />\n\n==== '''Homology''' ====\nThere are several identified [[Homology (biology)|homologs]] of the zc3h11b protein in a variety of species including various mammals, insects, and  amphibians.\n\n===== Paralogs =====\nCurrently, there is one [[Sequence homology|paralog]] of ZC3H11B in the same CCCH-type zinc finger family based on [[BLAST (biotechnology)|BLAST]] analysis (NCBI).\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Name\n!Species\n!NCBI accession number\n!Length (AA)\n!Protein identity\n|-\n|[[ZC3H11A]]\n|''[[Homo sapiens|H. sapiens]]''\n|[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/NP_001306167.1?report=genbank&log$=prottop&blast_rank=1&RID=9EECR6XS014 NP_001306167.1]\n|810\n|93.29%\n|}\n\n\nC12orf50 (''H. sapiens)'' has also been predicted as a paralog of ZC3H11B <ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":7\" />.\n<br />\n\n===== Orthologs =====\n\n\nThere are several species that have been found as having [[Sequence homology|orthologs]] to the zc3h11b protein in their genome based on BLAST analysis (NCBI).\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Name\n!Species\n!NCBI accession number\n!Length (AA)\n!Protein identity\n|-\n|ZC3H11A\n|''[[Chimpanzee|P. troglodytes]]''\n|[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/XP_016791924.1?report=genbank&log$=prottop&blast_rank=12&RID=9EDRWNJA014 XP_016791924.1]\n|810\n|93.29%\n|-\n|ZC3H11A\n|''[[Rhesus macaque|M. mulatta]]''\n|[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/NP_001247891.1?report=genbank&log$=prottop&blast_rank=32&RID=9EDRWNJA014 NP_001247891.1]\n|810\n|92.67%\n|-\n|ZC3H11A\n|''[[Wolf|C. lupus]]''\n|[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/XP_022271137.1?report=genbank&log$=prottop&blast_rank=78&RID=9EDRWNJA014 XP_022271137.1]\n|815\n|84.34%\n|-\n|ZC3H11A\n|''[[Cat|F. catus]]''\n|[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/XP_006942949.1?report=genbank&log$=prottop&blast_rank=81&RID=9EDRWNJA014 XP_006942949.1]\n|816\n|83.60%\n|-\n|ZC3H11A\n|''[[Horse|E. caballus]]''\n|[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/NP_001295209.1?report=genbank&log$=prottop&blast_rank=88&RID=9EDRWNJA014 NP_001295209.1]\n|815\n|83.70%\n|}\n\n\nZC3H11A (''[[Cattle|B. Taurus]]''), Zc3h11a (''[[House mouse|M. musculus]]''), Zc3h11a (''[[Brown rat|R. norvegicus]]''), ZC3H11A (''[[Chicken|G. gallus]]''), zc3h11a, (''[[Western clawed frog|X. tropicalis]]''), zc3h11a (''[[Zebrafish|D. rerio]]''), AT2G02160 (''[[Arabidopsis thaliana|A. thaliana]]''), ZC3H11A (''[[Housefly|M. domesticia]]''), zc3h11a (''[[Anolis carolinensis|A. carolinensis]]''), and ZC3H11A (''[[Wild boar|S. scrofa]]'') have also been predicted as orthologs of ZC3H11B <ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":7\" />.\n\n==== References ====\n{{Reflist}}<br />\n", "text_old": "'''ZC3H11B''' \n\nZinc finger CCCH-type containing protein 11B is a [[protein]] in humans that is encoded by the ZC3H11B [[gene]] <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/|title=Home - Gene - NCBI|website=www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. The zc3h11b gene is located on [[chromosome 1]], on the long arm, in band 4 section 1. This protein is also known as ZC3HDC11B. The zc3h11b gene is a total of 5,134 base pairs long, and the protein is 805 amino acids in length. The zc3h11b gene has 2 [[Exon|exons]] in total.\n\n<br />\n\n==== '''Clinical Significance''' ====\nCurrent research has identified ZC3H11B as [[Single-nucleotide polymorphism|single-nucleotide polymorphisms]] (SNPs) that are the most common genetic variation among groups with high [[Near-sightedness|myopia]] and corneal [[astigmatism]] <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Fan|first=Qiao|last2=Barathi|first2=Veluchamy A.|last3=Cheng|first3=Ching-Yu|last4=Zhou|first4=Xin|last5=Meguro|first5=Akira|last6=Nakata|first6=Isao|last7=Khor|first7=Chiea-Chuen|last8=Goh|first8=Liang-Kee|last9=Li|first9=Yi-Ju|last10=Lim|first10=Wan'e|last11=Ho|first11=Candice E. H.|date=2012|title=Genetic variants on chromosome 1q41 influence ocular axial length and high myopia|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22685421|journal=PLoS genetics|volume=8|issue=6|pages=e1002753|doi=10.1371/journal.pgen.1002753|issn=1553-7404|pmc=3369958|pmid=22685421}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Shah|first=Rupal L.|last2=Guggenheim|first2=Jeremy A.|last3=UK Biobank Eye and Vision Consortium|date=2018-12-01|title=Genome-wide association studies for corneal and refractive astigmatism in UK Biobank demonstrate a shared role for myopia susceptibility loci|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s00439-018-1942-8|journal=Human Genetics|language=en|volume=137|issue=11|pages=881\u2013896|doi=10.1007/s00439-018-1942-8|issn=1432-1203|pmc=PMC6267700|pmid=30306274}}</ref>. As of April 2020, there have been no other published association studies linking ZC3H11B with other conditions.\n<br />\n\n===== Myopia =====\nMyopia, also known as shortsightedness or nearsightedness, is a condition caused by a [[refractive error]] in which the shape of the eye is either elongated or the cornea is too curved <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aoa.org/patients-and-public/eye-and-vision-problems/glossary-of-eye-and-vision-conditions/myopia|title=Myopia (Nearsightedness)|website=www.aoa.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. In developed countries, this condition occurs in over 50% of the population with a high rate of occurrence among adults (80-90%) in East Asia and occurs approximately in 30% of the population in the United States <ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wu|first=Pei-Chang|last2=Huang|first2=Hsiu-Mei|last3=Yu|first3=Hun-Ju|last4=Fang|first4=Po-Chiung|last5=Chen|first5=Chueh-Tan|date=2016|title=Epidemiology of Myopia|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27898441|journal=Asia-Pacific Journal of Ophthalmology (Philadelphia, Pa.)|volume=5|issue=6|pages=386\u2013393|doi=10.1097/APO.0000000000000236|issn=2162-0989|pmid=27898441|via=}}</ref>.\n\nMyopia is categorized in two groups. The first of which comprises of people with low to medium amount of myopia, or simple myopia, and is diagnosed at 0 to -6 [[Dioptre|diopters]] and is treated with corrective lenses. The second is classified as high myopia and is diagnosed at greater than -6 diopters and typically are found in cases of [[retinal detachment]], [[macular degeneration]], and [[glaucoma]] <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fredrick|first=Douglas R|date=2002-05-18|title=Myopia|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1123161/|journal=BMJ : British Medical Journal|volume=324|issue=7347|pages=1195\u20131199|issn=0959-8138|pmc=1123161|pmid=12016188}}</ref>. \u00a0Myopia is considered as one of the leading causes of blindness and visual impairment in the world by the [[World Health Organization]] <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pararajasegaram|first=R.|date=1999|title=VISION 2020-the right to sight: from strategies to action|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10511033|journal=American Journal of Ophthalmology|volume=128|issue=3|pages=359\u2013360|doi=10.1016/s0002-9394(99)00251-2|issn=0002-9394|pmid=10511033|via=}}</ref>.\n\nAn elongated ocular [[Intraocular lens power calculation|axial length]] (AL), or distance from the anterior corneal surface to the [[retinal pigment epithelium]] <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bhardwaj|first=Veena|last2=Rajeshbhai|first2=Gandhi Parth|date=2013|title=Axial Length, Anterior Chamber Depth-A Study in Different Age Groups and Refractive Errors|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3843406/|journal=Journal of Clinical and Diagnostic Research : JCDR|volume=7|issue=10|pages=2211\u20132212|doi=10.7860/JCDR/2013/7015.3473|issn=2249-782X|pmc=3843406|pmid=24298478|via=}}</ref>, is a determinant of the development of myopia. A [[genome-wide association study]] conducted in a population of Chinese adults and children as well as Malay adults identified that ZC3H11B is associated with AL and high myopia <ref name=\":1\" />. There were ZC3H11B [[Messenger RNA|mRNA]] expression levels in the brain, placenta, neural retina, [[Retinal pigment epithelium|retina pigment epithelium]], and [[sclera]] with a greater decrease in quantity or [[Downregulation and upregulation|down-regulated]] expression levels in myopic eyes than non-myopic eyes. This identification was confirmed in another genome-wide association study along with the identification of additional significant [[Locus (genetics)|loci]] for AL of [[R-spondin 1|RSPO1]] (involved in [[Wnt signaling pathway|Wnt signaling]] or regulation of eyeball size), [[C3orf62|C3orf26]], ZNRF3 (involved in Wnt signaling), and [[ALPPL2]] <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cheng|first=Ching-Yu|last2=Schache|first2=Maria|last3=Ikram|first3=M.\u00a0Kamran|last4=Young|first4=Terri\u00a0L.|last5=Guggenheim|first5=Jeremy\u00a0A.|last6=Vitart|first6=Veronique|last7=MacGregor|first7=Stuart|last8=Verhoeven|first8=Virginie\u00a0J.M.|last9=Barathi|first9=Veluchamy\u00a0A.|last10=Liao|first10=Jiemin|last11=Hysi|first11=Pirro\u00a0G.|date=2013-08-08|title=Nine Loci for Ocular Axial Length Identified through Genome-wide Association Studies, Including Shared Loci with Refractive Error|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3772747/|journal=American Journal of Human Genetics|volume=93|issue=2|pages=264\u2013277|doi=10.1016/j.ajhg.2013.06.016|issn=0002-9297|pmc=3772747|pmid=24144296}}</ref>. Thus, this identification of shared association AL genes indicates that AL and refraction may be caused by different optic pathways. Additionally, a genome-wide association study in Chinese populations confirmed that ZC3H11B is a susceptibility gene for the development of high and extreme myopia <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tang|first=Shu Min|last2=Li|first2=Fen Fen|last3=Lu|first3=Shi Yao|last4=Kam|first4=Ka Wai|last5=Tam|first5=Pancy O. S.|last6=Tham|first6=Clement C.|last7=Pang|first7=Chi Pui|last8=Yam|first8=Jason C. S.|last9=Chen|first9=Li Jia|date=2019-07-12|title=Association of the ZC3H11B, ZFHX1B and SNTB1 genes with myopia of different severities|url=https://bjo.bmj.com/content/early/2019/07/12/bjophthalmol-2019-314203|journal=British Journal of Ophthalmology|language=en|doi=10.1136/bjophthalmol-2019-314203|issn=0007-1161|pmid=31300455}}</ref>.\n<br />\n\n===== Astigmatism =====\nAn astigmatism is a condition in which the curvature of the [[cornea]] or [[Lens (anatomy)|lens]] is abnormal <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aao.org/eye-health/diseases/what-is-astigmatism|title=What Is Astigmatism?|date=2018-08-31|website=American Academy of Ophthalmology|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. Astigmatisms can be classified as corneal astigmatism in which the corneal shape is irregular, lenticular astigmatism in which the lens shape is irregular, or refractive astigmatism. Astigmatism is typically treated with corrective lenses or surgery (such as [[LASIK]]) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.health.harvard.edu/a_to_z/astigmatism-a-to-z|title=Astigmatism|last=Publishing|first=Harvard Health|website=Harvard Health|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\nRefractive and corneal astigmatism may lead to the development of [[amblyopia]], or lazy eye, if left untreated. A genome-wide association study of individuals of European ancestry identified the ZC3H11B gene as significant for corneal astigmatism <ref name=\":2\" />. Additionally, there were two other loci were identified to demonstrate genome-wide significant association for corneal astigmatism, [[E3 ubiquitin ligase HERC2|HERC2]] and TSPAN10/[[NPLOC4]].\n<br />\n\n==== '''Protein''' ====\n\n===== Conserved Domains =====\nThe ZC3H11B protein has three [[Protein domain|conserved domains]]. These include [[zinc finger]] domains, which are one of the most common or abundant protein groups often involved in regulation of cellular processes <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cassandri|first=Matteo|last2=Smirnov|first2=Artem|last3=Novelli|first3=Flavia|last4=Pitolli|first4=Consuelo|last5=Agostini|first5=Massimiliano|last6=Malewicz|first6=Michal|last7=Melino|first7=Gerry|last8=Raschell\u00e0|first8=Giuseppe|date=2017-11-13|title=Zinc-finger proteins in health and disease|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/cddiscovery201771|journal=Cell Death Discovery|language=en|volume=3|issue=1|pages=1\u201312|doi=10.1038/cddiscovery.2017.71|issn=2058-7716}}</ref>, and [[coiled coil]] domains, which are a structurally conserved protien group present in all domains of life often involved in molecular spacing, [[Vesicle (biology and chemistry)|vesicle]] tethering, and [[DNA]] recognition and cleavage <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Truebestein|first=Linda|last2=Leonard|first2=Thomas A.|date=2016|title=Coiled\u2010coils: The long and short of it|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5082667/|journal=Bioessays|volume=38|issue=9|pages=903\u2013916|doi=10.1002/bies.201600062|issn=0265-9247|pmc=5082667|pmid=27492088|via=}}</ref>. Both the zinc finger and coiled coil domains are [[Conserved sequence|conserved]] in [[Eukaryote|eukaryotes]].\n\nZinc finger C3H1-type 1 is located from [[Amino acid|amino acids]] 2-29 ,and zinc finger C3H1-type 2 is located from amino acids 31-57 <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/A0A1B0GTU1|title=UniProtKB - A0A1B0GTU1 (ZC11B_HUMAN)|last=|first=|date=|website=UniProt|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. Zinc finger C3H1-type proteins have been identifed to interact with 3' region of untranslated [[Messenger RNA|mRNAs]] <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hall|first=Traci M Tanaka|date=2005-06-01|title=Multiple modes of RNA recognition by zinc finger proteins|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0959440X05000837|journal=Current Opinion in Structural Biology|series=Sequences and topology/Nucleic acids|language=en|volume=15|issue=3|pages=367\u2013373|doi=10.1016/j.sbi.2005.04.004|issn=0959-440X}}</ref>. Coiled coil is located from positions 403-423 amino acids of the protein <ref name=\":4\" /> .\n<br />\n\n===== Secondary Structure =====\nCurrently the [[Secondary structure of proteins|secondary structure]] of ZC3H11B is unknown. \n\nThe predicted secondary structure of ZC3H11B is a [[Protein structure prediction|loop]] secondary structure composition <ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://open.predictprotein.org/|title=PredictProtein|last=|first=|date=|website=PredictProtein|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, which are irregular secondary structures that connect two secondary structural elements and are able to change the direction of [[Peptide|polypeptide chain]] propagation <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dhar|first=Jesmita|last2=Chakrabarti|first2=Pinak|date=2015-06-01|title=Defining the loop structures in proteins based on composite \u03b2-turn mimics|url=https://academic.oup.com/peds/article/28/6/153/1445671|journal=Protein Engineering, Design and Selection|language=en|volume=28|issue=6|pages=153\u2013161|doi=10.1093/protein/gzv017|issn=1741-0126}}</ref>.  The loop is predicted to be exposed for [[Protein\u2013protein interaction|binding]] <ref name=\":5\" />.\n\n===== [[Post-translational modification|Post-Translational Modification]] =====\nZC3H11B is likely found in the nucleus <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psort.hgc.jp/form2.html|title=PSORT II Prediction|website=psort.hgc.jp|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. ZC3H11B is predicted to undergo various [[Protein phosphorylation|phosphorylations]], [[O-GlcNAcylations]], [[Glycation|glycations]], and [[O-linked glycosylation|O-glycosylations]] <ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbs.dtu.dk/services/|title=CBS Prediction Servers|website=www.cbs.dtu.dk|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\nExample of sites predicted for phosphorylation, a mechanism in which a [[phosphoryl group]] is added and important in biological regulation and other cellular processes <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nestler|first=Eric J.|last2=Greengard|first2=Paul|date=1999|title=Protein Phosphorylation is of Fundamental Importance in Biological Regulation|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK28063/|journal=Basic Neurochemistry: Molecular, Cellular and Medical Aspects. 6th edition|language=en}}</ref>, occur on 108, 149, 196,229, 290, and 330 <ref name=\":6\" />. Example of sites predicted for O-GlcNAcylations, a mechanism in which a [[Protein O-GlcNAc transferase|O-linked N-acetylglucosamine]] (O-GlcNAc) is added and important for regulation of cellular processes <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Xiaoyong|last2=Qian|first2=Kevin|date=2017|title=Protein O-GlcNAcylation: emerging mechanisms and functions|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28488703|journal=Nature Reviews. Molecular Cell Biology|volume=18|issue=7|pages=452\u2013465|doi=10.1038/nrm.2017.22|issn=1471-0080|pmc=5667541|pmid=28488703|via=}}</ref>, are 488, 744, and 732 <ref name=\":6\" />. Examples of sites predicted for glycations, a mechanism in which [[glucose]] binds with proteins and [[Lipid|lipids]], are 140, 359, 669, and 776 <ref name=\":6\" />. Example of sites predicted for O-glycosylation , a mechanism in which sugars or[[Monosaccharide|monosaccharides]] add to [[Hydroxy group|hydroxyl groups]] of proteins <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/biochemistry-genetics-and-molecular-biology/o-linked-glycosylation|title=O-Linked Glycosylation - an overview {{!}} ScienceDirect Topics|website=www.sciencedirect.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>, occur on 179 and 386 <ref name=\":6\" />.\n<br />\n\n==== '''Function''' ====\nThe ZC3H11B protein is expressed in various tissues including those of the [[Testicle|testis]], heart, leg, and [[Adrenal gland|adrenal]] <ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://monarchinitiative.org/gene/HGNC:25659#anatomy|title=Monarch Initiative Explorer|website=monarchinitiative.org|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. ZC3H11B is predicted to be involved in [[Metal-binding protein|metal ion binding]], a mechanism that involves combination of a [[Metal|metal ion]] or [[chelation]], as inferred from Electronic Association <ref name=\":0\" />.\n<br />\n\n==== '''Homology''' ====\nThere are several identified [[Homology (biology)|homologs]] of the zc3h11b protein in a variety of species including various mammals, insects, and  amphibians.\n\n===== Paralogs =====\nCurrently, there is one [[Sequence homology|paralog]] of ZC3H11B in the same CCCH-type zinc finger family based on [[BLAST (biotechnology)|BLAST]] analysis (NCBI).\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Name\n!Species\n!NCBI accession number\n!Length (AA)\n!Protein identity\n|-\n|[[ZC3H11A]]\n|''[[Homo sapiens|H. sapiens]]''\n|[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/NP_001306167.1?report=genbank&log$=prottop&blast_rank=1&RID=9EECR6XS014 NP_001306167.1]\n|810\n|93.29%\n|}\n\n\nC12orf50 (''H. sapiens)'' has also been predicted as a paralog of ZC3H11B <ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":7\" />.\n<br />\n\n===== Orthologs =====\n\n\nThere are several species that have been found as having [[Sequence homology|orthologs]] to the zc3h11b protein in their genome based on BLAST analysis (NCBI).\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Name\n!Species\n!NCBI accession number\n!Length (AA)\n!Protein identity\n|-\n|ZC3H11A\n|''[[Chimpanzee|P. troglodytes]]''\n|[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/XP_016791924.1?report=genbank&log$=prottop&blast_rank=12&RID=9EDRWNJA014 XP_016791924.1]\n|810\n|93.29%\n|-\n|ZC3H11A\n|''[[Rhesus macaque|M. mulatta]]''\n|[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/NP_001247891.1?report=genbank&log$=prottop&blast_rank=32&RID=9EDRWNJA014 NP_001247891.1]\n|810\n|92.67%\n|-\n|ZC3H11A\n|''[[Wolf|C. lupus]]''\n|[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/XP_022271137.1?report=genbank&log$=prottop&blast_rank=78&RID=9EDRWNJA014 XP_022271137.1]\n|815\n|84.34%\n|-\n|ZC3H11A\n|''[[Cat|F. catus]]''\n|[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/XP_006942949.1?report=genbank&log$=prottop&blast_rank=81&RID=9EDRWNJA014 XP_006942949.1]\n|816\n|83.60%\n|-\n|ZC3H11A\n|''[[Horse|E. caballus]]''\n|[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/NP_001295209.1?report=genbank&log$=prottop&blast_rank=88&RID=9EDRWNJA014 NP_001295209.1]\n|815\n|83.70%\n|}\n\n\nZC3H11A (''[[Cattle|B. Taurus]]''), Zc3h11a (''[[House mouse|M. musculus]]''), Zc3h11a (''[[Brown rat|R. norvegicus]]''), ZC3H11A (''[[Chicken|G. gallus]]''), zc3h11a, (''[[Western clawed frog|X. tropicalis]]''), zc3h11a (''[[Zebrafish|D. rerio]]''), AT2G02160 (''[[Arabidopsis thaliana|A. thaliana]]''), ZC3H11A (''[[Housefly|M. domesticia]]''), zc3h11a (''[[Anolis carolinensis|A. carolinensis]]''), and ZC3H11A (''[[Wild boar|S. scrofa]]'') have also been predicted as orthologs of ZC3H11B <ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":7\" />.\n\n\n\n{{Reflist}}<br />\n", "name_user": "GGGwork", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added header", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ZC3H11B"}
{"title_page": "Tomi Lahren", "text_new": "{{short description|American conservative political commentator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Tomi Lahren\n| image       = Tomi Lahren by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption     = Lahren in 2018\n| birth_name  = Tomi Rae Augustus Lahren\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1992|8|11|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Rapid City, South Dakota]], U.S.\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]]\n| occupation  = [[Vlog]]ger: ''Tomi Lahren's Final Thoughts''<br />Conservative political commentator\n| employer    = [[Fox News]]/[[Fox Nation]]\n| party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n}}\n\n'''Tomi Rae Augustus Lahren'''<ref name=\"Rapid City\">{{cite report|url=http://educationdocbox.com/docview/71/66070219/#file=/storage/71/66070219/66070219.pdf|title=Rapid City Area School District 51-4 Board of Education Meeting|date=June 3, 2010|type=Meeting minutes|accessdate=August 27, 2019|publisher=Rapid City Area Schools|place=Rapid City, South Dakota|page=11}}</ref>{{better source|date=March 2020}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|\u0252|m|i|_|\u02c8|l|\u00e6r|\u0259n}}; born August 11, 1992) is an American [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] political commentator and former [[Television presenter|television host]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/07/31/tomi-lahren-conservative-firebrand-bashes-obamacare-while-benefiting-from-it/|title=Tomi Lahren, conservative firebrand, bashes Obamacare while benefiting from it|last=Schmidt|first=Samantha|date=July 31, 2017|work=The Washington Post|access-date=February 27, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> She hosted ''Tomi'' on [[TheBlaze]], where she gained notice for her short video segments called \"final thoughts\", in which she frequently criticized [[Liberalism in the United States|liberal politics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/sep/23/tomi-lahren-conservative-white-power-barbie|title=The rise of Tomi Lahren, the media star lampooned as 'white power Barbie'|last=Wilson|first=Jason|date=September 23, 2016|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> Many of her videos became popular, with ''[[The New York Times]]'' describing her as a \"rising media star\".<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/04/business/media/tomi-lahren-young-vocal-and-the-rights-rising-media-star.html|title=Tomi Lahren: Young, Vocal and the Right's Rising Media Star|last=Bromwich|first=Jonah Engel|date=December 4, 2016|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Lahren was suspended from TheBlaze in March 2017 after saying in an interview on ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'' that she believed women should have [[legal protection of access to abortion|legal access to abortion]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Shortly thereafter, she began working for [[Great America PAC#Great America Alliance|Great America Alliance]], an advocacy organization that supports [[Donald Trump]],<ref name=\"wpgaa\" /> and, in August 2017, she joined [[Fox News]] as a contributor<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/fox-news-tomi-lahren-contributor-1202542708/|title=Fox News Signs Tomi Lahren as Contributor|journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=August 30, 2017|first=Joe|last=Otterson}}</ref> and now hosts a talk show on [[Fox Nation]].\n\n==Early life==\n{{Conservatism US}}\nLahren grew up in [[Rapid City, South Dakota]] and graduated from [[Central High School (Rapid City, South Dakota)|Central High School]] in 2010.<ref name=\"rcsept2014\">Hammond, Christy (September 21, 2014). [http://rapidcityjournal.com/lifestyles/local/rapid-city-woman-anchors-political-talk-show-at/article_a59b782a-2f96-5b4a-9dad-a7b920d4e79d.html Rapid City woman anchors political talk show at 22], ''[[Rapid City Journal]]''</ref><ref name=\"hschool\">Soderlin, Barbara (May 7, 2010). [http://rapidcityjournal.com/business/teens-gear-up-for-first-job-hunt/article_59f025bc-5949-11df-8e34-001cc4c03286.html Teens gear up for first job hunt], ''Rapid City Journal''</ref><ref name=\"Rapid City\"/> She is of [[German American|German]] and [[Norwegian American|Norwegian]] descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-38021995 |title=Tomi Lahren: the young Republican who's bigger than Trump on Facebook |publisher=BBC |date=November 29, 2016 |access-date=November 29, 2016}}</ref> Lahren graduated from [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]] in 2014 with a B.A. in broadcast journalism and political science.<ref name=\"FNC\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/fox-news-tomi-lahren-contributor-1202542708/|title=Fox News Signs Tomi Lahren as Contributor|first=Joe|last=Otterson|date=August 30, 2017|publisher=|access-date=August 30, 2017}}</ref> She also hosted and associate produced the university's political roundtable show ''The Scramble''.<ref name=\"scramble\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o2t08fFnNq8&list=PLOe3Rg-dJy_eeZ6GrSjLnkZTdoBPnG7R6 The Scramble - Episode 315], UNLV Journalism and Media Studies, youtube channel</ref> Lahren interned for [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] then-congresswoman [[Kristi Noem]] from South Dakota, serving as the first intern at Noem's Rapid City office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/politics/a8578782/tomi-lahren-facts-the-blaze-things-to-know/|title=Who Is Tomi Lahren? 10 Things You Need to Know About the 24-Year-Old Conservative Commentator.|date=March 16, 2017|publisher=|access-date=March 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHoping to find an internship in political commentary, Lahren applied to [[One America News Network]] (OANN), obtained an interview, and was instead offered the opportunity to host her own show. She moved to [[San Diego, California]] and began working for OANN. ''On Point with Tomi Lahren'' debuted in August 2014.<ref name=\"start\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TomiLahren/statuses/497807376930459648|title=Tomi Lahren on Twitter|publisher=|access-date=December 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"rcsept2014\" /><ref name=\"western\">Beattie, James (July 20, 2015). [http://www.westernjournalism.com/watch-news-anchor-gets-fed-up-with-obama-and-says-what-everyones-been-thinking-in-epic-rant/ Watch: News Anchor Gets Fed Up With Obama, Says What Everyone's Thinking In EPIC Rant], [[Western Journalism Center]]</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, a video of her commentary on the [[2015 Chattanooga shootings]] garnered widespread attention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2015/07/21/chattanooga-tomi-lahren-one-america-news-network-obama-middle-east/30497797/|title=TV host Tomi Lahren slams Obama's Middle East policy|last=Conley|first=Cole|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> On August 19, Lahren announced that she had completed her last show with OANN. She moved to Texas and began a new show with TheBlaze in November 2015. She became known for ending her program with three-minute segments called \"final thoughts\", in which she spoke extremely quickly. These segments became widely popular on social media, but have been called \"screeds\" and \"rants\".<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-38021995|title=Tomi Lahren: the young Republican who's bigger than Trump on Facebook|last=Wendling|first=Mike|date=November 30, 2016|publisher=|access-date=December 7, 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Lahren endorsed [[Marco Rubio]] for president in the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|Republican Party presidential primary]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/198655-new-video-lauds-marco-rubios-conservative-credentials|title=New video highlights Marco Rubio's conservative credentials - Florida Politics|date=January 14, 2016|work=Florida Politics|access-date=April 8, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=TheBlaze|title=Blue Wall: Why Tomi Supports Marco Rubio {{!}} \"Tomi\"|date=March 11, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2U1-sKhGSTY|access-date=April 9, 2017}}</ref> On November 30, Lahren appeared on ''[[The Daily Show with Trevor Noah]]'' for a 26-minute interview. Many critics compared her appearance to former host [[Jon Stewart]]'s friendly rivalry with [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2016/12/01/daily-show-trevor-noah-tomi-lahren-interview/94723818/|title=After that 'Daily Show' interview, is Tomi Lahren Trevor Noah's Bill O'Reilly?|first=Jayme|last=Deerwester|work=USA Today|date=December 1, 2016|access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/12/daily-show-debate-trevor-noah-tomi-lahren-donald-trump|title=''The Daily Show'' Just Got One Step Closer to Reviving the Spirit of Jon Stewart|first=Laura|last=Bradley|work=Vanity Fair|date=December 1, 2016|access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/trevor-noah-has-his-best-interview-yet-living-face-246725|title=Trevor Noah has his best interview yet with living Facebook screed Tomi Lahren|first=Sean|last=O'Neal|work=The A.V. Club|date=December 1, 2016|access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2017, Lahren made a guest appearance on ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'' in which she said that women should have access to [[abortion]] and that she would be a hypocrite if she supported both \"[[limited government]] and also government restrictions on abortion\".<ref name=dallas2>{{cite web |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/texas-politics/2017/06/15/tomi-lahren-conservative-much-harder-woman |title=Tomi Lahren: Being a conservative is much harder than being a woman |last=Cobler |first=Nicole |date=June 2017 |website=Dallas News}}</ref> TheBlaze's owner, [[Glenn Beck]], who is [[pro-life|anti-abortion]], criticized Lahren for her comments and suspended her with pay,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2017/03/20/glenn-beck-criticizes-commentator-tomi-lahren/99413066/|title=Commentator Tomi Lahren suspended from TheBlaze|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=March 20, 2017|first=Jessica|last=Estepa}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/tomi-lahren-banned-permanently-from-the-blaze-a7651071.html|title=Tomi Lahren 'banned permanently' from The Blaze|date=March 26, 2017|publisher=|access-date=April 19, 2017}}</ref> leading Lahren to file a [[wrongful termination]] suit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2017/04/07/tomi-lahren-sues-glenn-beck-the-blaze-for-wrongful-termination/100182952/ |title=Tomi Lahren sues Glenn Beck and The Blaze for wrongful termination |publisher=USA Today |date=April 7, 2017 |access-date=April 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=dallasnews>{{cite news|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/news/2017/04/07/tomi-lahren-sues-glenn-beck-blaze-wrongful-termination|title=Tomi Lahren sues Glenn Beck, The Blaze for wrongful termination over pro-choice stance|first=Naomi|last=Martin|work=The Dallas Morning News|date=April 7, 2017|access-date=April 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/news/tomi-lahren-sues-glenn-beck-for-wrongful-termination/ar-BBzxK84?fb_comment_id=1435213869862070_1435437269839730&comment_id=1435437269839730#f3c9d79fa9be59|title=Tomi Lahren Sues Glenn Beck For Wrongful Termination|access-date=April 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170409021301/http://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/news/tomi-lahren-sues-glenn-beck-for-wrongful-termination/ar-BBzxK84?fb_comment_id=1435213869862070_1435437269839730&comment_id=1435437269839730#f3c9d79fa9be59|archive-date=April 9, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The suit was settled under an agreement in which Lahren kept her Facebook page but removed videos she had made with TheBlaze.<ref name=wpsettlement>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/05/02/tomi-lahren-settles-lawsuit-with-glenn-beck-the-blaze-ending-abortion-comment-dust-up/|title=Tomi Lahren settles lawsuit with Glenn Beck, the Blaze, ending abortion comment dust-up|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=May 2, 2017|first=Derek|last=Hawkins}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Lahren began working in communications at Great America Alliance, an offshoot of [[Great America PAC]], a large pro-[[Donald Trump]] [[super PAC]] chaired by [[Newt Gingrich]] and [[Rudy Giuliani]]. Lahren described her role there as a \"side gig\" and said she would return to television as a commentator.<ref name=wpgaa>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/05/23/tomi-lahren-lands-new-gig-at-pro-trump-advocacy-group-after-settling-suit-with-the-blaze/|title=Tomi Lahren lands new gig at pro-Trump advocacy group after settling suit with the Blaze|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=May 23, 2017|first=Samantha|last=Schmidt}}</ref> In August 2017, Lahren joined [[Fox News]] as a contributor.<ref name=\"FNC\" /> She now hosts a talk show on [[Fox Nation]] called First Thoughts.\n\n==Political views==\n[[File:Tomi Lahren (44210703612).jpg|right|thumb|Lahren speaking at a campaign rally for U.S. Senate candidate [[Kelli Ward]] in August 2018]]\nLahren describes herself as a \"constitutional conservative\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://college.usatoday.com/2017/03/17/in-which-we-discover-that-tomi-lahren-is-pro-choice/|title=Conservative host Tomi Lahren came out as pro-choice|last=McGough|first=Cameron|date=March 18, 2017|publisher=|access-date=March 18, 2017}}</ref> She has said that she is a commentator, not a journalist,<ref name=\"guardianbarbie\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/sep/23/tomi-lahren-conservative-white-power-barbie|title=The rise of Tomi Lahren, the media star lampooned as 'white power Barbie'|first=Jason|last=Wilson|date=September 23, 2016|work=The Guardian}}</ref> and that her shows are not about presenting news neutrally, but about commentary and \"mak[ing] the news\".<ref name=BBC /> ''The Daily Beast'' described her as a \"right-wing provocateur\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/tomi-lahren-lives-in-alternate-universe-where-fox-news-never-attacked-michelle-obama|title=Tomi Lahren Lives in Alternate Universe Where Fox News Never Attacked Michelle Obama|last=Burke|first=Timothy|date=August 22, 2018|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=August 27, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nLahren has been described as an \"anti-feminist who admires strong women.\"<ref name=\"BBC\" /> Lahren has said that while she does not consider herself a feminist,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/texas/2017/04/13/will-lay-play-dead-ever-tomi-lahren-tells-nightline|title='I will not lay down and play dead \u2014 ever,' Tomi Lahren tells 'Nightline' - Texas|date=April 13, 2017|work=Dallas News|access-date=April 19, 2017}}</ref> she believes in women's empowerment and looks up to various women from both the political left and the political right.<ref name=\"BBC\" /> In March 2017, Lahren said she was [[pro-choice|pro-abortion rights]], sparking criticism from a number of [[Anti-abortion movements|anti-abortion]] writers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schmidt|first1=Samantha|title='I'm pro-choice,' says Tomi Lahren: 'Stay out of my guns, and you can stay out of my body'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/03/20/tomi-lahren-on-why-shes-pro-choice-stay-out-of-my-guns-and-you-can-stay-out-of-my-body-as-well/|access-date=March 20, 2017|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=March 18, 2017}}</ref> TheBlaze owner Glenn Beck, among others, noted that Lahren had previously publicly said she was anti-abortion, in addition to numerous other inconsistencies on other issues.<ref name=dallasnews /> Soon thereafter, Lahren told ''[[Playboy]]'' that she had always supported abortion rights as a matter of national law but was personally against abortion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playboy.com/articles/tomi-lahren-playboy-conversation|title=Tomi Lahren Exclusively Talks To Playboy After Her Blaze Fallout|date=May 2, 2017|work=Playboy|access-date=August 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171221185716/http://www.playboy.com/articles/tomi-lahren-playboy-conversation|archive-date=December 21, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/05/07/shut-up-tomi-lahren-profile-215108|title=Tomi Lahren Will Not Shut Up|last=Guinto|first=Joseph|website=POLITICO Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\nLahren is in favor of [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|same-sex marriage]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/03/20/tomi-lahren-on-why-shes-pro-choice-stay-out-of-my-guns-and-you-can-stay-out-of-my-body-as-well/|title='I'm pro-choice,' says Tomi Lahren: 'Stay out of my guns, and you can stay out of my body'|last=Schmidt|first=Samantha|date=March 20, 2017|website=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=May 18, 2019}}</ref>  While in college, Lahren wrote a feature for the ''[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]'' about a classmate who had turned to stripping to support herself.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/education/lessons-by-day-lap-dances-by-night-for-students/|title=Lessons by day, lap dances by night for students|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=April 15, 2012|accessdate=August 27, 2019|last=Lahren|first=Tomi|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120417160944/http://www.lvrj.com/living/lessons-by-day-lap-dances-by-night-for-students-147481565.html|archivedate=April 17, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"5 things\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/college/2016/12/02/5-things-to-know-about-tomi-lahren/37425343/|title=5 things to know about Tomi Lahren|last=Funke|first=Daniel|work=USA Today|accessdate=August 27, 2019|date=December 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nLahren's commentaries have been described by critics as racist or race-baiting, which she disputes.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> In July 2016, Lahren posted a tweet comparing the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement to the [[Ku Klux Klan]].<ref name=BBC /> Tens of thousands of people signed a [[Change.org]] petition in response asking for her to be fired from ''TheBlaze''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://college.usatoday.com/2016/07/13/over-56000-people-want-tomi-lahren-fired-from-the-blaze-after-kkk-tweet/|title=Over 56,000 people want Tomi Lahren fired from TheBlaze after KKK tweet|author=Tulp, Sophia|work=[[USA Today]]|date=July 13, 2016|publisher=|access-date=December 7, 2016}}</ref> The petition was unsuccessful. In August 2016, she released a video criticizing [[NFL]] [[quarterback]] [[Colin Kaepernick]], who had been protesting [[police brutality]] by [[U.S. national anthem protests (2016\u2013present)|kneeling during the playing of the national anthem before football games]].<ref name=nyt />\n\nIn August 2018, at a political rally for [[Kelli Ward]], Lahren warned against voters electing 'RINOs' ([[Republican In Name Only|Republicans in name only]]) like Senators [[John McCain]] and [[Jeff Flake]] into Congress.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutzler |first1=Alexandra |title=Tomi Lahren calls John McCain 'RINO' on same day his family announced he was stopping cancer treatment |url=https://www.newsweek.com/tomi-lahren-calls-john-mccain-rino-same-day-senator-stops-cancer-treatment-1090659 |work=[[Newsweek]] |access-date=August 26, 2018}}</ref> Lahren was criticized as cruel and disrespectful as McCain was in very poor health; that day he discontinued medical treatment for brain cancer, and he died the next day. Many people have criticized Lahren for her behavior including former Fox News anchor [[Greta Van Susteren]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Haring |first1=Bruce |title=Fox News Contributor Tomi Lahren Criticized For Dig At John McCain |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/fox-news-contributor-tomi-lahren-criticized-for-dig-at-john-mccain-1202452275/ |publisher=[[Deadline (magazine)|Deadline]] |access-date=August 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=John McCain: Tributes as Vietnam veteran and six-term senator dies at 81 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-45313697 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |access-date=August 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Lahren said that the \"highlight\" of her Thanksgiving had been watching [[United States Border Patrol]] fire [[teargas]] at migrants trying to illegally cross over the Mexico\u2013United States border.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailydot.com/layer8/tomi-lahren-thanksgiving/|title=Tomi Lahren says migrants getting tear-gassed was the 'highlight' of her Thanksgiving|date=November 26, 2018|work=The Daily Dot|access-date=November 26, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/fox-news-tomi-lahren-migrants-tear-gas-thanksgiving-1231582|title=Fox News contributor Tomi Lahren says seeing migrants get hit with tear gas was the \"highlight\" of her Thanksgiving|date=November 26, 2018|work=Newsweek|access-date=November 27, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/fox-news-tomi-lahren-claiming-immigrants-carry-diseases-compared-to-nazi-propaganda-1.6721649|title=Fox News' Tomi Lahren Claiming Immigrants Carry Diseases Compared to Nazi Propaganda|date=2018-12-06|work=Haaretz|access-date=2018-12-09|language=en}}</ref> In December 2018, she ran a Fox Nation segment focusing on how members of a [[Central American migrant caravans|Central American migrant caravan]] that had been stopped in Mexico that year were carrying diseases; she listed several unconfirmed cases of HIV/AIDS and chicken pox to support the claim.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/fox-nations-tomi-lahren-accuses-migrants-of-bringing-hiv-tb|title=Fox Nation's Tomi Lahren Accuses Migrants of Bringing HIV, TB|date=2018-12-04|website=The Daily Beast|language=en|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref> That same month, she urged President Trump to shut down the government to force Congress to fund the construction of a wall on the Mexico\u2013United States border.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/fox-and-friends-stunned-by-trumps-loss-to-pelosi-on-wall|title='Fox & Friends' 'Stunned' by Trump's Loss to Pelosi on Border Wall Funding|last=Messer|first=Olivia|date=2018-12-19|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=2018-12-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Tomi Lahren}}\n\n* [http://insider.foxnews.com/tomi-lahren-final-thoughts Fox News Insider: \"Tomi Lahren's Final Thoughts\"]\n* {{cite web|url = http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/05/07/shut-up-tomi-lahren-profile-215108|publisher = [[Politico magazine]]|title = Profile: Tomi Lahren Will Not Shut Up|author = Joseph Guinto|date = May 7, 2017}}\n\n{{Fox News personalities}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lahren, Tomi}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Norwegian descent]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American social commentators]]\n[[Category:American television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Anti-immigration politics in the United States]]\n[[Category:Christians from South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Female critics of feminism]]\n[[Category:Fox News people]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:People from Dallas]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Rapid City, South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populism in the United States]]\n[[Category:South Dakota Republicans]]\n[[Category:University of Nevada, Las Vegas alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American conservative political commentator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Tomi Lahren\n| image       = Tomi Lahren by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption     = Lahren in 2018\n| birth_name  = Tomi Rae Augustus Lahren\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1992|8|11|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Rapid City, South Dakota]], U.S.\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]]\n| occupation  = [[Vlog]]ger: ''Tomi Lahren's Final Thoughts''<br />Conservative political commentator\n| employer    = [[Fox News]]/[[Fox Nation]]\n| party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n}}\n\n'''Tomi Rae Augustus Lahren'''<ref name=\"Rapid City\">{{cite report|url=http://educationdocbox.com/docview/71/66070219/#file=/storage/71/66070219/66070219.pdf|title=Rapid City Area School District 51-4 Board of Education Meeting|date=June 3, 2010|type=Meeting minutes|accessdate=August 27, 2019|publisher=Rapid City Area Schools|place=Rapid City, South Dakota|page=11}}</ref>{{better source|date=March 2020}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|\u0252|m|i|_|\u02c8|l|\u00e6r|\u0259n}}; born August 11, 1992) is an American [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] political commentator and former [[Television presenter|television host]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/07/31/tomi-lahren-conservative-firebrand-bashes-obamacare-while-benefiting-from-it/|title=Tomi Lahren, conservative firebrand, bashes Obamacare while benefiting from it|last=Schmidt|first=Samantha|date=July 31, 2017|work=The Washington Post|access-date=February 27, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> She hosted ''Tomi'' on [[TheBlaze]], where she gained notice for her short video segments called \"final thoughts\", in which she frequently criticized [[Liberalism in the United States|liberal politics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/sep/23/tomi-lahren-conservative-white-power-barbie|title=The rise of Tomi Lahren, the media star lampooned as 'white power Barbie'|last=Wilson|first=Jason|date=September 23, 2016|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> Many of her videos went [[Viral video|viral]], with ''[[The New York Times]]'' describing her as a \"rising media star\".<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/04/business/media/tomi-lahren-young-vocal-and-the-rights-rising-media-star.html|title=Tomi Lahren: Young, Vocal and the Right's Rising Media Star|last=Bromwich|first=Jonah Engel|date=December 4, 2016|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Lahren was suspended from TheBlaze in March 2017 after saying in an interview on ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'' that she believed women should have [[legal protection of access to abortion|legal access to abortion]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Shortly thereafter, she began working for [[Great America PAC#Great America Alliance|Great America Alliance]], an advocacy organization that supports [[Donald Trump]],<ref name=\"wpgaa\" /> and, in August 2017, she joined [[Fox News]] as a contributor<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/fox-news-tomi-lahren-contributor-1202542708/|title=Fox News Signs Tomi Lahren as Contributor|journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=August 30, 2017|first=Joe|last=Otterson}}</ref> and now hosts a talk show on [[Fox Nation]].\n\n==Early life==\n{{Conservatism US}}\nLahren grew up in [[Rapid City, South Dakota]] and graduated from [[Central High School (Rapid City, South Dakota)|Central High School]] in 2010.<ref name=\"rcsept2014\">Hammond, Christy (September 21, 2014). [http://rapidcityjournal.com/lifestyles/local/rapid-city-woman-anchors-political-talk-show-at/article_a59b782a-2f96-5b4a-9dad-a7b920d4e79d.html Rapid City woman anchors political talk show at 22], ''[[Rapid City Journal]]''</ref><ref name=\"hschool\">Soderlin, Barbara (May 7, 2010). [http://rapidcityjournal.com/business/teens-gear-up-for-first-job-hunt/article_59f025bc-5949-11df-8e34-001cc4c03286.html Teens gear up for first job hunt], ''Rapid City Journal''</ref><ref name=\"Rapid City\"/> She is of [[German American|German]] and [[Norwegian American|Norwegian]] descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-38021995 |title=Tomi Lahren: the young Republican who's bigger than Trump on Facebook |publisher=BBC |date=November 29, 2016 |access-date=November 29, 2016}}</ref> Lahren graduated from [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]] in 2014 with a B.A. in broadcast journalism and political science.<ref name=\"FNC\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/fox-news-tomi-lahren-contributor-1202542708/|title=Fox News Signs Tomi Lahren as Contributor|first=Joe|last=Otterson|date=August 30, 2017|publisher=|access-date=August 30, 2017}}</ref> She also hosted and associate produced the university's political roundtable show ''The Scramble''.<ref name=\"scramble\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o2t08fFnNq8&list=PLOe3Rg-dJy_eeZ6GrSjLnkZTdoBPnG7R6 The Scramble - Episode 315], UNLV Journalism and Media Studies, youtube channel</ref> Lahren interned for [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] then-congresswoman [[Kristi Noem]] from South Dakota, serving as the first intern at Noem's Rapid City office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/politics/a8578782/tomi-lahren-facts-the-blaze-things-to-know/|title=Who Is Tomi Lahren? 10 Things You Need to Know About the 24-Year-Old Conservative Commentator.|date=March 16, 2017|publisher=|access-date=March 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHoping to find an internship in political commentary, Lahren applied to [[One America News Network]] (OANN), obtained an interview, and was instead offered the opportunity to host her own show. She moved to [[San Diego, California]] and began working for OANN. ''On Point with Tomi Lahren'' debuted in August 2014.<ref name=\"start\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TomiLahren/statuses/497807376930459648|title=Tomi Lahren on Twitter|publisher=|access-date=December 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"rcsept2014\" /><ref name=\"western\">Beattie, James (July 20, 2015). [http://www.westernjournalism.com/watch-news-anchor-gets-fed-up-with-obama-and-says-what-everyones-been-thinking-in-epic-rant/ Watch: News Anchor Gets Fed Up With Obama, Says What Everyone's Thinking In EPIC Rant], [[Western Journalism Center]]</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, a video of her commentary on the [[2015 Chattanooga shootings]] garnered widespread attention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2015/07/21/chattanooga-tomi-lahren-one-america-news-network-obama-middle-east/30497797/|title=TV host Tomi Lahren slams Obama's Middle East policy|last=Conley|first=Cole|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> On August 19, Lahren announced that she had completed her last show with OANN. She moved to Texas and began a new show with TheBlaze in November 2015. She became known for ending her program with three-minute segments called \"final thoughts\", in which she spoke extremely quickly. These segments became widely popular on social media, but have been called \"screeds\" and \"rants\".<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-38021995|title=Tomi Lahren: the young Republican who's bigger than Trump on Facebook|last=Wendling|first=Mike|date=November 30, 2016|publisher=|access-date=December 7, 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Lahren endorsed [[Marco Rubio]] for president in the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|Republican Party presidential primary]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/198655-new-video-lauds-marco-rubios-conservative-credentials|title=New video highlights Marco Rubio's conservative credentials - Florida Politics|date=January 14, 2016|work=Florida Politics|access-date=April 8, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=TheBlaze|title=Blue Wall: Why Tomi Supports Marco Rubio {{!}} \"Tomi\"|date=March 11, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2U1-sKhGSTY|access-date=April 9, 2017}}</ref> On November 30, Lahren appeared on ''[[The Daily Show with Trevor Noah]]'' for a 26-minute interview. Many critics compared her appearance to former host [[Jon Stewart]]'s friendly rivalry with [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2016/12/01/daily-show-trevor-noah-tomi-lahren-interview/94723818/|title=After that 'Daily Show' interview, is Tomi Lahren Trevor Noah's Bill O'Reilly?|first=Jayme|last=Deerwester|work=USA Today|date=December 1, 2016|access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/12/daily-show-debate-trevor-noah-tomi-lahren-donald-trump|title=''The Daily Show'' Just Got One Step Closer to Reviving the Spirit of Jon Stewart|first=Laura|last=Bradley|work=Vanity Fair|date=December 1, 2016|access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/trevor-noah-has-his-best-interview-yet-living-face-246725|title=Trevor Noah has his best interview yet with living Facebook screed Tomi Lahren|first=Sean|last=O'Neal|work=The A.V. Club|date=December 1, 2016|access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2017, Lahren made a guest appearance on ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'' in which she said that women should have access to [[abortion]] and that she would be a hypocrite if she supported both \"[[limited government]] and also government restrictions on abortion\".<ref name=dallas2>{{cite web |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/texas-politics/2017/06/15/tomi-lahren-conservative-much-harder-woman |title=Tomi Lahren: Being a conservative is much harder than being a woman |last=Cobler |first=Nicole |date=June 2017 |website=Dallas News}}</ref> TheBlaze's owner, [[Glenn Beck]], who is [[pro-life|anti-abortion]], criticized Lahren for her comments and suspended her with pay,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2017/03/20/glenn-beck-criticizes-commentator-tomi-lahren/99413066/|title=Commentator Tomi Lahren suspended from TheBlaze|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=March 20, 2017|first=Jessica|last=Estepa}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/tomi-lahren-banned-permanently-from-the-blaze-a7651071.html|title=Tomi Lahren 'banned permanently' from The Blaze|date=March 26, 2017|publisher=|access-date=April 19, 2017}}</ref> leading Lahren to file a [[wrongful termination]] suit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2017/04/07/tomi-lahren-sues-glenn-beck-the-blaze-for-wrongful-termination/100182952/ |title=Tomi Lahren sues Glenn Beck and The Blaze for wrongful termination |publisher=USA Today |date=April 7, 2017 |access-date=April 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=dallasnews>{{cite news|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/news/2017/04/07/tomi-lahren-sues-glenn-beck-blaze-wrongful-termination|title=Tomi Lahren sues Glenn Beck, The Blaze for wrongful termination over pro-choice stance|first=Naomi|last=Martin|work=The Dallas Morning News|date=April 7, 2017|access-date=April 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/news/tomi-lahren-sues-glenn-beck-for-wrongful-termination/ar-BBzxK84?fb_comment_id=1435213869862070_1435437269839730&comment_id=1435437269839730#f3c9d79fa9be59|title=Tomi Lahren Sues Glenn Beck For Wrongful Termination|access-date=April 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170409021301/http://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/news/tomi-lahren-sues-glenn-beck-for-wrongful-termination/ar-BBzxK84?fb_comment_id=1435213869862070_1435437269839730&comment_id=1435437269839730#f3c9d79fa9be59|archive-date=April 9, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The suit was settled under an agreement in which Lahren kept her Facebook page but removed videos she had made with TheBlaze.<ref name=wpsettlement>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/05/02/tomi-lahren-settles-lawsuit-with-glenn-beck-the-blaze-ending-abortion-comment-dust-up/|title=Tomi Lahren settles lawsuit with Glenn Beck, the Blaze, ending abortion comment dust-up|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=May 2, 2017|first=Derek|last=Hawkins}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Lahren began working in communications at Great America Alliance, an offshoot of [[Great America PAC]], a large pro-[[Donald Trump]] [[super PAC]] chaired by [[Newt Gingrich]] and [[Rudy Giuliani]]. Lahren described her role there as a \"side gig\" and said she would return to television as a commentator.<ref name=wpgaa>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/05/23/tomi-lahren-lands-new-gig-at-pro-trump-advocacy-group-after-settling-suit-with-the-blaze/|title=Tomi Lahren lands new gig at pro-Trump advocacy group after settling suit with the Blaze|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=May 23, 2017|first=Samantha|last=Schmidt}}</ref> In August 2017, Lahren joined [[Fox News]] as a contributor.<ref name=\"FNC\" /> She now hosts a talk show on [[Fox Nation]] called First Thoughts.\n\n==Political views==\n[[File:Tomi Lahren (44210703612).jpg|right|thumb|Lahren speaking at a campaign rally for U.S. Senate candidate [[Kelli Ward]] in August 2018]]\nLahren describes herself as a \"constitutional conservative\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://college.usatoday.com/2017/03/17/in-which-we-discover-that-tomi-lahren-is-pro-choice/|title=Conservative host Tomi Lahren came out as pro-choice|last=McGough|first=Cameron|date=March 18, 2017|publisher=|access-date=March 18, 2017}}</ref> She has said that she is a commentator, not a journalist,<ref name=\"guardianbarbie\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/sep/23/tomi-lahren-conservative-white-power-barbie|title=The rise of Tomi Lahren, the media star lampooned as 'white power Barbie'|first=Jason|last=Wilson|date=September 23, 2016|work=The Guardian}}</ref> and that her shows are not about presenting news neutrally, but about commentary and \"mak[ing] the news\".<ref name=BBC /> ''The Daily Beast'' described her as a \"right-wing provocateur\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/tomi-lahren-lives-in-alternate-universe-where-fox-news-never-attacked-michelle-obama|title=Tomi Lahren Lives in Alternate Universe Where Fox News Never Attacked Michelle Obama|last=Burke|first=Timothy|date=August 22, 2018|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=August 27, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nLahren has been described as an \"anti-feminist who admires strong women.\"<ref name=\"BBC\" /> Lahren has said that while she does not consider herself a feminist,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/texas/2017/04/13/will-lay-play-dead-ever-tomi-lahren-tells-nightline|title='I will not lay down and play dead \u2014 ever,' Tomi Lahren tells 'Nightline' - Texas|date=April 13, 2017|work=Dallas News|access-date=April 19, 2017}}</ref> she believes in women's empowerment and looks up to various women from both the political left and the political right.<ref name=\"BBC\" /> In March 2017, Lahren said she was [[pro-choice|pro-abortion rights]], sparking criticism from a number of [[Anti-abortion movements|anti-abortion]] writers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schmidt|first1=Samantha|title='I'm pro-choice,' says Tomi Lahren: 'Stay out of my guns, and you can stay out of my body'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/03/20/tomi-lahren-on-why-shes-pro-choice-stay-out-of-my-guns-and-you-can-stay-out-of-my-body-as-well/|access-date=March 20, 2017|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=March 18, 2017}}</ref> TheBlaze owner Glenn Beck, among others, noted that Lahren had previously publicly said she was anti-abortion, in addition to numerous other inconsistencies on other issues.<ref name=dallasnews /> Soon thereafter, Lahren told ''[[Playboy]]'' that she had always supported abortion rights as a matter of national law but was personally against abortion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playboy.com/articles/tomi-lahren-playboy-conversation|title=Tomi Lahren Exclusively Talks To Playboy After Her Blaze Fallout|date=May 2, 2017|work=Playboy|access-date=August 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171221185716/http://www.playboy.com/articles/tomi-lahren-playboy-conversation|archive-date=December 21, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/05/07/shut-up-tomi-lahren-profile-215108|title=Tomi Lahren Will Not Shut Up|last=Guinto|first=Joseph|website=POLITICO Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\nLahren is in favor of [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|same-sex marriage]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/03/20/tomi-lahren-on-why-shes-pro-choice-stay-out-of-my-guns-and-you-can-stay-out-of-my-body-as-well/|title='I'm pro-choice,' says Tomi Lahren: 'Stay out of my guns, and you can stay out of my body'|last=Schmidt|first=Samantha|date=March 20, 2017|website=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=May 18, 2019}}</ref>  While in college, Lahren wrote a feature for the ''[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]'' about a classmate who had turned to stripping to support herself.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/education/lessons-by-day-lap-dances-by-night-for-students/|title=Lessons by day, lap dances by night for students|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=April 15, 2012|accessdate=August 27, 2019|last=Lahren|first=Tomi|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120417160944/http://www.lvrj.com/living/lessons-by-day-lap-dances-by-night-for-students-147481565.html|archivedate=April 17, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"5 things\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/college/2016/12/02/5-things-to-know-about-tomi-lahren/37425343/|title=5 things to know about Tomi Lahren|last=Funke|first=Daniel|work=USA Today|accessdate=August 27, 2019|date=December 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nLahren's commentaries have been described by critics as racist or race-baiting, which she disputes.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> In July 2016, Lahren posted a tweet comparing the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement to the [[Ku Klux Klan]].<ref name=BBC /> Tens of thousands of people signed a [[Change.org]] petition in response asking for her to be fired from ''TheBlaze''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://college.usatoday.com/2016/07/13/over-56000-people-want-tomi-lahren-fired-from-the-blaze-after-kkk-tweet/|title=Over 56,000 people want Tomi Lahren fired from TheBlaze after KKK tweet|author=Tulp, Sophia|work=[[USA Today]]|date=July 13, 2016|publisher=|access-date=December 7, 2016}}</ref> The petition was unsuccessful. In August 2016, she released a video criticizing [[NFL]] [[quarterback]] [[Colin Kaepernick]], who had been protesting [[police brutality]] by [[U.S. national anthem protests (2016\u2013present)|kneeling during the playing of the national anthem before football games]].<ref name=nyt />\n\nIn August 2018, at a political rally for [[Kelli Ward]], Lahren warned against voters electing 'RINOs' ([[Republican In Name Only|Republicans in name only]]) like Senators [[John McCain]] and [[Jeff Flake]] into Congress.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutzler |first1=Alexandra |title=Tomi Lahren calls John McCain 'RINO' on same day his family announced he was stopping cancer treatment |url=https://www.newsweek.com/tomi-lahren-calls-john-mccain-rino-same-day-senator-stops-cancer-treatment-1090659 |work=[[Newsweek]] |access-date=August 26, 2018}}</ref> Lahren was criticized as cruel and disrespectful as McCain was in very poor health; that day he discontinued medical treatment for brain cancer, and he died the next day. Many people have criticized Lahren for her behavior including former Fox News anchor [[Greta Van Susteren]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Haring |first1=Bruce |title=Fox News Contributor Tomi Lahren Criticized For Dig At John McCain |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/fox-news-contributor-tomi-lahren-criticized-for-dig-at-john-mccain-1202452275/ |publisher=[[Deadline (magazine)|Deadline]] |access-date=August 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=John McCain: Tributes as Vietnam veteran and six-term senator dies at 81 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-45313697 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |access-date=August 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Lahren said that the \"highlight\" of her Thanksgiving had been watching [[United States Border Patrol]] fire [[teargas]] at migrants trying to illegally cross over the Mexico\u2013United States border.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailydot.com/layer8/tomi-lahren-thanksgiving/|title=Tomi Lahren says migrants getting tear-gassed was the 'highlight' of her Thanksgiving|date=November 26, 2018|work=The Daily Dot|access-date=November 26, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/fox-news-tomi-lahren-migrants-tear-gas-thanksgiving-1231582|title=Fox News contributor Tomi Lahren says seeing migrants get hit with tear gas was the \"highlight\" of her Thanksgiving|date=November 26, 2018|work=Newsweek|access-date=November 27, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/fox-news-tomi-lahren-claiming-immigrants-carry-diseases-compared-to-nazi-propaganda-1.6721649|title=Fox News' Tomi Lahren Claiming Immigrants Carry Diseases Compared to Nazi Propaganda|date=2018-12-06|work=Haaretz|access-date=2018-12-09|language=en}}</ref> In December 2018, she ran a Fox Nation segment focusing on how members of a [[Central American migrant caravans|Central American migrant caravan]] that had been stopped in Mexico that year were carrying diseases; she listed several unconfirmed cases of HIV/AIDS and chicken pox to support the claim.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/fox-nations-tomi-lahren-accuses-migrants-of-bringing-hiv-tb|title=Fox Nation's Tomi Lahren Accuses Migrants of Bringing HIV, TB|date=2018-12-04|website=The Daily Beast|language=en|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref> That same month, she urged President Trump to shut down the government to force Congress to fund the construction of a wall on the Mexico\u2013United States border.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/fox-and-friends-stunned-by-trumps-loss-to-pelosi-on-wall|title='Fox & Friends' 'Stunned' by Trump's Loss to Pelosi on Border Wall Funding|last=Messer|first=Olivia|date=2018-12-19|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=2018-12-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Tomi Lahren}}\n\n* [http://insider.foxnews.com/tomi-lahren-final-thoughts Fox News Insider: \"Tomi Lahren's Final Thoughts\"]\n* {{cite web|url = http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/05/07/shut-up-tomi-lahren-profile-215108|publisher = [[Politico magazine]]|title = Profile: Tomi Lahren Will Not Shut Up|author = Joseph Guinto|date = May 7, 2017}}\n\n{{Fox News personalities}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lahren, Tomi}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Norwegian descent]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American social commentators]]\n[[Category:American television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Anti-immigration politics in the United States]]\n[[Category:Christians from South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Female critics of feminism]]\n[[Category:Fox News people]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:People from Dallas]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Rapid City, South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populism in the United States]]\n[[Category:South Dakota Republicans]]\n[[Category:University of Nevada, Las Vegas alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Volunteer1234", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(became popular)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tomi_Lahren"}
{"title_page": "List of Grand Dukes of Bosnia", "text_new": "{{See also|List of rulers of Bosnia}}\nThe title '''''[[Grand duke|Grand Duke]] of Bosnia''''' ({{lang-bs|Veliki Vojvoda Bosanski}}) was a court title in the [[Kingdom of Bosnia]], bestowed by the King to highest military commanders, usually reserved for most influential and most capable among highest Bosnian nobility.<ref name=\"Kurtovi\u0107-Vojvoda u Bosni-2005\">{{cite web |last1=Kurtovi\u0107 |first1=Esad |title=Vojvoda u srednjovjekovnoj Bosni - ZNANSTVENI SKUP Posve\u0107en arheologu i povjesni\u010daru Pavlu An\u0111eli\u0107u (1920-1985) |url=https://www.academia.edu/31218806/Vojvoda_u_srednjovjekovnoj_Bosni |website=academia.edu |publisher=Franjeva\u010dka teologija Sarajevo |accessdate=15 April 2020 |location=Sarajevo |language=en |format=pdf |date=15 October 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"Fine-Late-Medieval-Balkans\">{{cite book |last=Fine |first=John Van Antwerp |title=The Late Medieval Balkans: A Critical Survey from the Late Twelfth Century to the Ottoman Conquest |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QDFVUDmAIqIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |year=1994 |publisher=University of Michigan Press |isbn=0-472-08260-4  |access-date= 20 October 2018}}</ref> To interpret it as an office post rather than a court rank could be more accurate.<ref name=\"Kurtovi\u0107-Veliki-vojvoda-bosanski-Sandalj-Hrani\u0107\">{{cite book|last1=Kurtovi\u0107|first1=Esad|title=Veliki vojvoda bosanski Sandalj Hrani\u0107 Kosa\u010da|publisher=Institut za istoriju Sarajevo|date=2009|isbn=978-9958-649-01-1|edition=Historijske monografije; knj. 4|url=http://www.iis.unsa.ba/pdf/kurtovic_sandalj_hranic_kosaca.pdf|accessdate=10 January 2016|language=Bosnian|format=.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305184319/http://www.iis.unsa.ba/pdf/kurtovic_sandalj_hranic_kosaca.pdf|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Grand Dukes of Bosnia ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Picture\n! <sup>Title</s