{"title_page": "Rod El Farag", "text_new": "'''Rod El Farag''' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u0648\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0631\u062c}}, {{IPA-arz|\u027eo\u02d0d el\u02c8f\u0251\u027e\u0251\u0261<!--no [d\u02e4] in Egyptian Arabic-->}}; also spelled '''Road El Farag''', '''Road Elfarag''' or '''Road Alfarag''') is an administrative region forming about one third of  [[Shobra]] in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]]. Rod El Farag neighbours the [[River Nile]] to the west, [[Boulaq]] to the south, [[Shobra (administrative region)]] to the east and [[Elsahel]] to the north.  [[Rough Guides]] notes that like neighbouring districts, Rod El Farag is generally overcrowded (170,000 residents per square kilometre).<ref>[http://www.roughguides.com/website/travel/destination/content/default.aspx?titleid=11&xid=idh469154864_0218 Bulaq, Shobra and Road El Farag], [[Rough Guides]].</ref>\n\n[[File:\u0645\u064a\u0646\u0627\u0621 \u0631\u0648\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0631\u062c \u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646.jpg|thumb|Old Rod El Farag]]\n\nHistorically, Rod El Farag has been a residential area for centuries and was known in the early twentieth century for its [[night club]]s.  For many years, Rod El Farag was home to Cairo's biggest fruit and vegetable market and the world-famous El-Nozah candy shop, started in 1940.{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}{{Failed verification|date=May 2010}} This candy shop was famous{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}} for its home-made [[ice cream]],<ref>[http://www.roughguides.com/website/travel/destination/content/default.aspx?titleid=11&xid=idh569162528_0219 Introduction to Egypt], Rough Guides.</ref> though it relocated to an area on the outskirts of [[Greater Cairo]].\n\nThe Rod El Farag market used to be the largest in all of Egypt, drawing regional farmers and traders to settle in the area.<ref>[http://www.aljazeeratalk.net/english/content/view/76/29/ AljazeeraTalk.net]{{Verify credibility|date=May 2010}}</ref> The area where the market used to stand now hosts Rod El Farag Cultural Palace.<ref>Nehad Selaiha, [http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/473/cu3.htm Back to Rod El-Farag], ''[http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/ Ahram Weekly]'', Egypt.</ref>\n\nThis district also contains good infrastructure, including the French school \"Notre Dame des Apotres.\"  Located on the [[corniche]] is the Arkadia Mall, which contains stores such as Mobcco and the Trianon confectionery and cafe.\n\n== Rod El Farag Bridge ==\nThe Rod El Farag Bridge over the [[Nile]] river, which is part of the [[Tahya Misr Axis]] crossing the Egyptian capital of [[Cairo]], designed by [[ACE Moharram Bakhoum]] and built by the Egyptian company [[Arab Contractors]], is the world's widest [[cable-stayed bridge]]<ref>http://en.wataninet.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Image_9-3.jpeg</ref> built over the course of 4 years until it was completed in 2019, achieving the [[Guinness World Record]] with a width of 67.3 meters<ref name=\"egypt_today_bridge_record\">{{cite web |title=Egypt's Rod al-Farag Axis featured in Guinness World Records as widest suspension bridge |url=https://www.egypttoday.com/Article/1/70434/Egypt-s-Rod-al-Farag-Axis-featured-in-Guinness-World |website=Egypt Today |accessdate=17 May 2019 |ref=egypt_today_bridge_record}}</ref><ref name=\"al_ahram_bridge\">{{cite web |title=Egypt's Sisi opens mega Rod El-Farag road, world's widest causeway |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContentP/1/331651/Egypt/Egypts-Sisi-opens-mega-Rod-ElFarag-road;-the-world.aspx |website=Al-Ahram |accessdate=17 May 2019 |ref=al_ahram_bridge}}</ref>. The 540 meters long bridge has 6 lanes in each direction, has suspension towers which are 92 meters high and 160 suspension cables to hold the bridge. Currently, it is becoming a major tourist attraction in Cairo, where visitors can cross the side pedestrian passageways which have panoramic views of the banks of the Nile and a glass floor see-through walkway where visitors can walk over the Nile<ref name=\"arab_contractors_bridge\">{{cite web |title=President Abdel Fattah El Sisi inaugurated \"Tahya Misr\" Axis and the Arab Contractors Company received Guinness World Records Certificate for \"Tahya Misr\" Bridge the World's Widest Cable Stayed Bridge |url=http://www.arabcont.com/English/News/Release-2019-1374.aspx |website=The Arab Contractors Company |accessdate=17 May 2019 |ref=arab_contractors_bridge}}</ref><ref name=\"egypt_army_bridge\">{{cite web |title=Lifelines of Hope (documentary) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cLq-5iii4RA |website=YouTube |publisher=The Egyptian Armed Forces |accessdate=17 May 2019 |ref=egypt_army_bridge}}</ref><ref name=\"dotmasr_bridge_video\">{{cite web |title=Watch: Egyptians' happiness after passing over the Rod El Farag Bridge and it's glass walkway |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ABRXKq-Y8hA |website=YouTube |publisher=Dot Masr (Youm7) |accessdate=17 May 2019 |ref=dotmasr_bridge_video}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Districts of Cairo}}\n\n{{coord|30|04|34|N|31|14|23|E|region:EG_type:city_source:kolossus-svwiki|display=title}}\n", "text_old": "'''Rod El Farag''' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u0648\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0631\u062c}}, {{IPA-arz|\u027eo\u02d0d el\u02c8f\u0251\u027e\u0251\u0261<!--no [d\u02e4] in Egyptian Arabic-->}}; also spelled '''Road El Farag''', '''Road Elfarag''' or '''Road Alfarag''') is an administrative region forming about one third of  [[Shobra]] in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]]. Rod El Farag neighbours the [[River Nile]] to the west, [[Boulaq]] to the south, [[Shobra (administrative region)]] to the east and [[Elsahel]] to the north.  [[Rough Guides]] notes that like neighbouring districts, Rod El Farag is generally overcrowded (170,000 residents per square kilometre).<ref>[http://www.roughguides.com/website/travel/destination/content/default.aspx?titleid=11&xid=idh469154864_0218 Bulaq, Shobra and Road El Farag], [[Rough Guides]].</ref>\n\n[[File:\u0645\u064a\u0646\u0627\u0621 \u0631\u0648\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0631\u062c \u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646.jpg|thumb|Old Rod El Farag]]\n\nHistorically, Rod El Farag has been a residential area for centuries and was known in the early twentieth century for its [[night club]]s.  For many years, Rod El Farag was home to Cairo's biggest fruit and vegetable market and the world-famous El-Nozah candy shop, started in 1940.{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}{{Failed verification|date=May 2010}} This candy shop was famous{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}} for its home-made [[ice cream]],<ref>[http://www.roughguides.com/website/travel/destination/content/default.aspx?titleid=11&xid=idh569162528_0219 Introduction to Egypt], Rough Guides.</ref> though it relocated to an area on the outskirts of [[Greater Cairo]].\n\nThe Rod El Farag market used to be the largest in all of Egypt, drawing regional farmers and traders to settle in the area.<ref>[http://www.aljazeeratalk.net/english/content/view/76/29/ AljazeeraTalk.net]{{Verify credibility|date=May 2010}}</ref> The area where the market used to stand now hosts Rod El Farag Cultural Palace.<ref>Nehad Selaiha, [http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/473/cu3.htm Back to Rod El-Farag], ''[http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/ Ahram Weekly]'', Egypt.</ref>\n\nThis district also contains good infrastructure, including the French school \"Notre Dame des Apotres.\"  Located on the [[corniche]] is the Arkadia Mall, which contains stores such as Mobcco and the Trianon confectionery and cafe.\n\n== Rod El Farag Bridge ==\nThe Rod El Farag Bridge over the [[Nile]] river, which is part of the [[Tahya Misr Axis]] crossing the Egyptian capital of [[Cairo]] and built by the Egyptian company [[Arab Contractors]], is the world's widest [[cable-stayed bridge]]<ref>http://en.wataninet.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Image_9-3.jpeg</ref> built over the course of 4 years until it was completed in 2019, achieving the [[Guinness World Record]] with a width of 67.3 meters<ref name=\"egypt_today_bridge_record\">{{cite web |title=Egypt's Rod al-Farag Axis featured in Guinness World Records as widest suspension bridge |url=https://www.egypttoday.com/Article/1/70434/Egypt-s-Rod-al-Farag-Axis-featured-in-Guinness-World |website=Egypt Today |accessdate=17 May 2019 |ref=egypt_today_bridge_record}}</ref><ref name=\"al_ahram_bridge\">{{cite web |title=Egypt's Sisi opens mega Rod El-Farag road, world's widest causeway |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContentP/1/331651/Egypt/Egypts-Sisi-opens-mega-Rod-ElFarag-road;-the-world.aspx |website=Al-Ahram |accessdate=17 May 2019 |ref=al_ahram_bridge}}</ref>. The 540 meters long bridge has 6 lanes in each direction, has suspension towers which are 92 meters high and 160 suspension cables to hold the bridge. Currently, it is becoming a major tourist attraction in Cairo, where visitors can cross the side pedestrian passageways which have panoramic views of the banks of the Nile and a glass floor see-through walkway where visitors can walk over the Nile<ref name=\"arab_contractors_bridge\">{{cite web |title=President Abdel Fattah El Sisi inaugurated \"Tahya Misr\" Axis and the Arab Contractors Company received Guinness World Records Certificate for \"Tahya Misr\" Bridge the World's Widest Cable Stayed Bridge |url=http://www.arabcont.com/English/News/Release-2019-1374.aspx |website=The Arab Contractors Company |accessdate=17 May 2019 |ref=arab_contractors_bridge}}</ref><ref name=\"egypt_army_bridge\">{{cite web |title=Lifelines of Hope (documentary) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cLq-5iii4RA |website=YouTube |publisher=The Egyptian Armed Forces |accessdate=17 May 2019 |ref=egypt_army_bridge}}</ref><ref name=\"dotmasr_bridge_video\">{{cite web |title=Watch: Egyptians' happiness after passing over the Rod El Farag Bridge and it's glass walkway |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ABRXKq-Y8hA |website=YouTube |publisher=Dot Masr (Youm7) |accessdate=17 May 2019 |ref=dotmasr_bridge_video}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Districts of Cairo}}\n\n{{coord|30|04|34|N|31|14|23|E|region:EG_type:city_source:kolossus-svwiki|display=title}}\n", "name_user": "Ibrahimsabotaleb120", "label": "safe", "comment": "added designer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_El_Farag"}
